Keighley, Yorishire}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\insrsid11799755\charrsid16072257 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-461\li461\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin461\itap0\pararsid11799755 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\fs20\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Could you tell me how many years you lived in the house where you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well roughly eight. I should imagine I would be eight year old when we left there. Yes.;;
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 That was a back to back house wasn't it?-
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 And it was a - a - it was back to back - attic, bedroom, living room, scullery, like on the top of the cellar steps, and the cellar.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you move in 1908?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well - we moved into Rawlings Street, that's just across the way, owing to the fact that we were a little overcrowded. There's no doubt about that. And the house at that time could be rented. They were - advertised to rent at that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 They were new houses were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh no, no. But they was houses that were rented and of course it - it cropped up that this came. And - of course we moved into there.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So you moved into Rawlings Street to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15663822\charrsid12214547 accommodate}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  all seven children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - I think it was more or less to start to get away from the single house that got to be.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 How long did you stay at Rawlings Street?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well I should imagine, as fars as me memory takes me, around about two year. Something like that, it could be a month or two more or less.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Where did you move to then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Then we went from there back up to Springbank into Brier Street, I think there were those three. Now we went there owing to the fact that this was a bigger house. It had - it had a big attic. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15663822\charrsid12214547 And - two good size bedrooms, a sitting room - living room, kitchen, cellar and this accommodated us far, far better. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Plus that also was a house to rent, advertised to rent.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 That would take us up to about 1919 would it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well that - yes, that took me - up - easily to 1919. Because I remember - that I lived up there when I went to - to start work in the mill, in 1912.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 And you stayed there 'til about the end of the first world war did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 I stayed at - I stayed there until - about 1922. That's - that's when I went and joined - the railway, I moved to Derbyshire.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So most of these moves were to get larger houses, each time you moved into a slightly bigger one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes. That's true, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Could you tell me how many brothers and sisters you had and how they were spaced?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - roughly there's three year between - all of us, the seven of us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 There were seven children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes. And - if you want the names there was Frank, Hilda, Norah, myself, Wilfred, Agnes and David.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So you had three brothers and three sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15663822\charrsid12214547 That\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Can you tell me how old our father was when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 How old he was when I was born? Well - I doubt very much - whether I could tell.
 How old he would be, owing to the fact - unless I had to look at - the death certificate. I could tell you that but I'd have to - and discover the - yes. Yes, I can - I can - yes, I can find that out, by looking in the paper, if I'd have thought I'd have
 had the papers down you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Could you tell me where he came from originally?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Me dad? Yes, he was born in a - a little place called Brinklow near Rugby in - Warwickshire.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Can you tell me what his occupation was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - before - he came to this part of the globe he was a gardener for the Earl of Craven in Warwickshire. That's right.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 He was a gardener from leaving school was he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15663822\charrsid12214547 Well he was a gardener I should imagine - as soon as he was old enough to work because in those da
ys they had to - to do to be high- falluting didn't they. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Now - he left there - and went onto the railway owing to the possibility and probability of getting more money - moving and that's how he come to come to Keighley - ultimately. He worked at - he wor
ked at Water Horton and various places round Birmingham before ever he came to - to Keighley. This was of course a long time before ever I was though of.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 And he worked for the railway around Rugby did he before he came to work for the railway at Keighley?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 That's right. And then he worked for the railway for the old Midland Railway. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What was his job with the Midland?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - he'd have all - he'd - he'd - work his way up from all kinds of job but he was what they called a relief rail
wayman. And in those days they - they relieved - oh station maters downwards. Or - porters upwards. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So whoever was short he filled their job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes, he - that's right, that was his job as far as my memory takes me which goes back - to the ear
liest days, because he used to take us down to see the trains you see, down - oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did he do this relief railwayman job until he retired?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes, he - he - and he retired - when he was sixty-five. Now I wouldn't like to say - when that was but -
 he was retired - thirty - I wouldn't like to say, because - he worked a little while on the railway - after I came back to Keighley, twenty-five and - thirty-five. I should say somewhere about thirty-two or three. I can reckon that up from - when he - ye
s.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So he was a gardener and then he was a relief railwayman, and as a relief railwayman he acted as }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10574403\charrsid12214547 stationmaster}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  and porter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 They - yes, they relieved - yes, if there was relief they worked it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Would he relieve signalmen as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 He -
 he never - he did attempt to go into the signalling grade but - it was too tied, he didn't like being tied into one place. So he - he never made a success of the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15663822\charrsid12214547 signalling}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  side of it
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 When he was a relief railwayman did he move about a lot?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes.;
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Or was it always around Keighley?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes, he - he worked at every station, I should imagine, in - in - my dad would work on every station between Keighley, }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15663822\charrsid12214547 Morecambe}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  and - as far as Wellington and that way and - I should imagine - Leeds a
nd - all round that - nearly every station there is round this part, that was attached at that time to the Midland Railway. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did he have to live away?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 He used to go into what they called lodgings. They had like places where they used to g
o lodging. And - however in the - how they did I do not know 'cos a magnificent of - pay was about sixteen shillings a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 And you didn't get an allowance for being away from home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well if they did it wouldn't be much above a shilling a night or something desperate like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you remember whether he did any casual or part time jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Me dad? The only hobby he had was - he used to keep - a few hens on the bank side that is now on the preservation society - property between Darringe and Ingrow, you can see the hut that my brother built, it's still on there. That -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 A sort of allotment he had did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes, he had an allotment at one time down where they've built }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15663822\charrsid12214547 Haggas's
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  mill in the Holme. But now of course }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15663822\charrsid12214547 Wilkinson\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  has 
taken all that over, it's all - I remember that being taken away, but that was taken away with him - from him - I should imagine - somewhere probably after or during the - the first world war. Because I - I hated every minute of it - having to go down the
re.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 To help him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Aye. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 But he didn't have any paid part time or casual jobs did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh no. No, in those days the - the work was twelve hour day. Six o'clock in the morning -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 He wouldn't have much time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh no, you see, b
eing shift work - twelve hours, it took him in to day and night, he was continuously either going to work, coming home - there were many a time when we - children, we didn't even see him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you remember your father ever being out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 No. N
ot out of work, I remember them being on strike a few days in 1911. There was a railway strike and miners strike in 1911, I remember them - marching through Keighley on one of these so called meet - marching to a meeting. And in these days of course, as y
o
u'll know, politics were very - what shall I say - rife, if a man was seen with a - a red lapel they were ready to crucify him. But I do remember that and I can remember at the same time the miners - had these - hurdy-gurdies - playing the music collectin
g pennies. The barrel organs, yes. I used to love them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 They were pushing it along with the procession?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well they - they }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15663822\charrsid12214547 went}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  round to get the coppers to help them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 They went round the streets collecting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes. Yes. And it was to hel
p - I think it was the miners that were really out at that time but there was a railway strike - 1911. It didn't go on very long.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 I've heard about strikes in 1911 }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15663822\charrsid12214547 from}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  people involved in the engineering shops, would this be the same strike?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well
 - I can only remember it from my dad's point of view because - he was out of work and he was like a militant worker and of course - I remember when they walked Keighley because I walked with them as a child, I can remember this quite plainly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did it close the railway down at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 I should imagine more or less, but it didn't go on for so long as - you know - to - to remember. It would close down, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you remember how old your mother was when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Now - this again w
ill have to be proved by the papers - owing to the fact that - I have a feeling that me - me mother would be probably - seventy-nine years younger than my - than me dad.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you know where she came from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes. She was born in a little place called }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15663822\charrsid12214547 Shrimpling}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  - near Bury St Edmonds, in Suffolk. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Had she any jobs before she married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
That - I wouldn't really - like to be able to say, for the simple reason - that these places were - little villages. And - and everybody - that could do a
nything had to either work for the squire of the village, which meant service, and I have a feeling that when me mother came to this part of the globe she came to work in the mill and lived at Oakworth. They came to live at Oakworth. And my sister Hilda w
as born at Oakworth. But where - no, I couldn't tell you. But I do know that she was Oakworth born.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 She came from }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15663822\charrsid12214547 Shrimpling}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  near Bury St Edmunds?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You're not sure }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2171094\charrsid12214547 of}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  any jobs that she did before she was married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well I don't - if she did any it would be more - a laundry sort of worker for the - byt the people that - the farm people and that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 How did she come to live in Keighley, did she come here when she married your father or did she come with her parents, did they all more 
here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
No, I - I - I think when she came I think she must have come more or less - half a minute - now - me - I remember - her mother, now they called her Page, that's why I carry the middle name. Now, I'd a grandmother that lived in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15663822\charrsid12214547 Briton}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  Street, up
 Springbank, which is next to Hazel Street. And she had a brother that lived in Pickles Street. So it's quite possible that she came owing to the fact that her parents come this way. Now, this is going back long before I was born, and I do remember - me g
r
andmother Page and me mother's brother, who was of course my Uncle Harry. And - her - her mother, my grandmother, took in railwaymen as lodgers that came to work - round here on this principle you see. And I think that's how she came to be - probably her 
own mother and father came - to Keighley on this business through the railway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you think her father had worked on the railway down in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15663822\charrsid12214547 Shrimp ling}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 I don't re - I don't recollect my - he was a miller, in Suffolk. He had one of these windmills t
hat ground - ground corn. And I have a feeling that probably he died and - and the family came this way. Owing to - you see, in villages like Shimpling - and the little places like Brinklow, all there were were the squires and the farmers and - you had to
 do as you was told
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 When your mother came to live in Keighley with her mother, you don't know of any jobs she did up here do you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 No - as - the most of anything that I know is me mother had a full time job looking after her family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 She never spoke of the time previous to when she was married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
No, no. No, No, I don't remember - that - I have a feeling that if she did anything she probably go work in the mill for a while, before she married. And that would be at Oakworth I should imagine
 because - if - when they got married at the first they lived at Oakworth then and - and I should think Frank and Hilda was born at Oakworth.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 She never worked after she was married, she was always busy looking after the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh ye, full time job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 She never had any time for part time jobs did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 No, no, no, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 The house that you lived in longest when you were a child would actually be Hazel Street?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes. That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You only lived at Brier Street a year or so before leaving school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well that's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 I think we'd better ask about Hazel Street, you've already told me something about it haven't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 It was a back to back with an attic?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes, there was an attic and of course the b
oy - I can remember - the boys sleeping in the attic. It was - 'cos like it was the biggest room in the house really because it went over the two bedrooms. Yes, I remember the - the boys like sleeping up there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 How many bedrooms did you have besides the attic?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 There'd be only one bedroom but I should imagine it might have been portioned but I do not remember you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You were only about eight when you moved?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You had an attic which was used as a bedroom and another a bedroom and then a living room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 That's right, not as big as this. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 And there was a kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
There was a - there was like a - a scullery - the - the cellar head type you see, you was at the sink and that - the cellar steps, then a cella
r. Aye. And of course the cellar, that's where we used to have - they had - their copper you know to do their washing and that and of course we used to have the baths and that down there - yes. The only place where you could have them really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did anyone else besides your parents and brothers and sisters live in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh no. No. There were - there were - there weren't room for us never mind anyone else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did your mother pay anyone to help in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 There was - one time - I do re
member - and I think it was more or less probably after Hilda started working the mill and all that, she did have - a woman come to help her once a week to do the washing, 'cos there was tremendous washing. And - that's the only help that she did have and
 - and in those days you know it was - there was no electric washers, it was all manual labour. Washing and twining and - hard work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You just remember this one lady coming in - how often would she come in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh once a week. That's right. And - this
 - to me it was nearly what you could call, I would call it, nearly an all day job for the simple reason that you had to wash for - for - for seven or eight - nine of us. And of course bedding and that, there was a tremendous wash.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you remember this lady at all who came in to help your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes, I remember her name and they called her Mrs Taft.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 She simply helped with the washing, she didn't do any cleaning or anything?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 She used to come to help me mother do this washing for the s
imple reason that I think the woman herself went round doing this - as a living. And probably would make a better living out of it than she would have done going to work in a mill, but - it was a lot harder work, it was terrible hard work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 She'd go to different houses every day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 I should imagine so, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you remember how you got on with her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Oh very - oh very well, I - oh yes, I think that the point is that it - when she came in the first place more than probably it started by - in 
a - in a sympathetic way to help. But in those days, no one had - had any money, everybody wanted money and of course whatever money she got off me mother it wouldn't be much 'cos me mother hadn't much to - to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 But she would be paid?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes, there'd be some payment, there'd be bound to be some payment, the woman couldn't do - gone on like it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you remember what she used to call your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well I - I think that - well me mother's name were Mary but she always got called Polly for s
ome reason, I really think that they called - I think I can remember - they called - she used to call her by her - her first name. And they was quite friendly, it wasn't - it was no - work, you come to work for me, me mother couldn't afford to be that way
, me mother were grateful for the assistance that were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15663822\charrsid12214547 given}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
 her, and probably paid out what she could afford and the - the woman was quite prepared to accept that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you remember what you called her, did you call her Mrs Taft?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well I always
 a called her Mrs Taft, like I mean she was - to me, I mean, she were a wonderful person, I - I mean I believe you know that when she came and all that I thought she was someone - different altogether. I always called her - I can remember her quite well.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So all the washing was done at home by your mother and this lady?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Oh yes. But this wash - I mean - I should imagine me mother did more washing every day. In some form or other. But this - was like as you could every week a big wash.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did your mother or father mend or make the family's clothes?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well, me dad didn't do any - any - any mending, it was illegal for a man to ever use needle and cotton in those days, I mean, he would have been looked upon as being something out of this world. B
ut me mother, yes. Me mother made me trousers out of me father's railway trousers. And I can remember her making them. And she had an old Singer sewing machine, and unfortunately the Singer people don't make the machines today like they did then. And ag -
 and she even made me a jacket to wear. Now, if she made me them she made them for the others.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Would she mend clothes as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Mend 'em? Yes, she did mend 'em. There was darned and patched and - and of course everybody else were in the same thing
 so no one thought a lot about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you ever get new clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
New clothes? I can't remember - to any marked extent, getting new clothes as such, they always seemed to me either - been made or - shall we say, handed down.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 From your older brother was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 In some mysterious way - they came along and we were proud to be - we only got to put them on at Sunday you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Your better things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes. And - and that was it. But I can't remember - being measured or made with a suit - oh, 'til I was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You don't remember going to a shop and buying anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh no. No. All these - these things were nearly out of - out of this world, you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15663822\charrsid12214547 couldn\rquote t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So most of your clothes were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 second-hand}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 I should imagine so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You don't remember about the girls, what they got, do you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well - no. I rather thing - I rather think that some of the girls' clothes would come from a friend that - worked up at Haggas' mill. You know Haggas' do you. Up the mills and Redhall - Sir Jo
hn Clough and all that, there was one or two people in there that was rather friendly with my - mother and I have a feeling that probably some of them clothes come from there for the girls. But I've no proof. But I certainly don't think they could go - bu
ying them.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 From a shop?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 No, not - not at that time. If it was it was done in some way, of course, as I said being a boy I couldn't care less about them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What about shoes, did you get new ones or }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 second-hand}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - we did get the
 occasional new shoes, but of course - as - as the feet got bigger the ones that - they fit came in. But we were clogs. Oh yes, we were clogs. And - the boys had like steel caps on the front of the toes and the girls had brass, you see. Oh yes, and of cou
r
se if - if they wanted to put brass toe plates on the boys we wouldn't have 'em because they would say - they're going to make us into girls you see. In - in those days when no one had any money there was this silly bit of pride. And we used to go to the 
c
obblers and have irons put on the shoe - on the clogs. And it runs about tuppence, and I think - I think we used to go and have these clogs put on - I do - I never recollect - paying any money to have the - the clogs ironed so me mother must have had a sy
stem of paying at the weekend or when dad got his pay or when she were lucky enough to have any money to pay it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you remember your father ever actually making you any shoes or clogs or repairing them for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 I don't - I don't recollect me dad
 - really - repairing it because as I say he had such a - a full time job. But - as soon as I could put heels and irons on me own - clogs, I used to do a little bit of that myself. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you father ever help your mother by either cleaning or coo
king, washing up, making fires, decorating, repairs to the house or improvements to the house, do you remember him doing any of those?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 I - I'm-afraid I don't remember me dad doing much of anything like that. If he - if he had his spare time it was either in his - garden }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 or}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
 - this hen thing. He didn't do much. He did help - occasionally - in some - probably the harder work like scraping the - no, me - me mother used to do that until 1918. And from 1918 onwards up to 1963, I did it, for every one of my family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You did all the decorating?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
All the lot. I don't - for me family and me very near friends. I didn't go out doing it. I did it - to help them and I loved doing it, but in 1963 when me leg started to play me up - and the doctors told me I 
- give up, that was it. But from 1918 onwards I did it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 But you don't remember your father doing any of these things?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Not - not -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You don't remember him making the fires in the morning before he went out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh he - he might - he might 
have laid a fire you see but there was many a time; when he'd be up and away at four o'clock in the morning. Oh yes, he - he did jobs like that, light the fire because there was old - old fireplaces and - and he'd clean the fireplace. Oh yes, he - he - he
 was a very handy man in a house. You see. And we brought - and we've been brought up to be the same, we can all look after ourselves in the house. But - his time was limited.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you remember when you were very small, him ever dressing and undressing y
ou, bathing you, reading to you or telling you stories or taking you out without; your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well he used to - he used to take us out - to - to see the - the trains and that. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 He was railway made and I believe this is where I got - some of my inclination for railway work. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Oh he used to take me to various stations and especially up the Worth Valley. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 
And I used to sit and write and - and pretend that I was the big noise on the station and - I loved that, and he'd take - he'd take us - on the short trai
n rides which to us was - oh - I suppose riding from Ingrow to Oakworth was a tremendous long way in those days. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Oh yes, he used to take us about that way, take us up onto the moor when he was off.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Would that be at the weekends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - it be - anytime when he was off. You see, he used to work - mostly weekends and holiday times I mean that was there busy time.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So he would take you out sometimes without your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes. Yes, he was a good - he was a good father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did he ever look after you when she was out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - no, you see, when - when me dad - when me dad was out he was at work or down in his }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 garden}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  and - and of course occasionally in those days they used to get down to what I call the church and they - every - every ma
n used to drink. That were one his big failings, he liked his drink. And of course - there was times when they'd burst out with this when money became very scarce and they couldn't. And no doubt there would be some upheavals in the family which we didn't 
h
ear or see. And that - that helped to keep people poor because nearly all men at that time who - spent most of their money and their time in the pub. But - let me be fair to him, it were his only - occasionally when he used to burst out and - and that was
 it. He were, mind you he was a worker, he never - he never broke any time. Worker and - and he was a good father.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You don't remember your mother ever going out and leaving your father in charge of the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 No, not really - not really. She us
ed to have to go out shopping but you see, there was always an elder sister. We was never left on our own. Oh no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you have any }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 tasks}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  you had to carry out regularly at home to help your mother and father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh my - yes, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 we}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  had - we - the - 
the coal was in the cellar, that had to be brought up in a bucket. I firewood had to be chopped. That were my - that were one of my jobs. In the old days there were no such things as - chrome knives and forks, these had to be cleaned and - and we used to 
have to take it in our turns. The boys. And clean the shoes. Now the girls, they - they had all the - the washing up, the washing and - all that. That were a girl's job, it wasn't a boy's. Yes. We were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 segregated}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 How long did you continue to do these jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 After you left school, did you still do it then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
More or less - when I - when I went to start going to work, you see, there was - the younger brother came up and we used to do it between us then it got so as everybody had to d
o their own, you see, as you got a bit older you used to go on strike and do your own and all that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 But you still brought coal up and chopped wood?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes, we - oh things like that you see we didn't - these things were - were instilled into us. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 
And if - and if me mother was a - bit off colour, which she was sometimes, she had some very, very - terrible headaches and they used to go on two or three days you know and that well I - I - I could go and make - make the bed, I could do hou
sework, I could help in that way. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 And I used to - to do that. But we all did. If you understand what I mean, these are things that - that was just a natural - part of our life. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you remember the older children helping the younger children with 
things they found difficult such as dressing or eating or did they look after them in any other way?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well - let - more or less you - you do - the elder ones helped to bring the - the younger ones p. My sister Norah, we're still very close, she used 
to take me to - go to school with me, she mothered me and I used to rebel against it and all that but - yes, they - when it came to being - the most of anything in regards to being bathed until - I was old enough to bath myself, it was me mother and I can
 
always remember me mother, she always used to sing to me while - yes. And I can remember songs that she used to sing even today. Such as Thora, my Task, and those kind of things, come into the garden Maud. All the - I can still - picture them. Although I 
was only a - a babe. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 Because as soon as we was able to do and look after ourselves, we had to do for ourselves. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you remember ever the younger children helping the older ones in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well, in quite a - in - in quite a natural way, o
wing to the fact that you see - when I - when I was born no doubt - the two girls they nursed me. And of - yes, and then of course as the other came along - when - who followed me - Wilf come along, to me he'd be a bit of a nuisance, but - he was me broth
er and - we played with one another. And believe me - home life was home life then. You played - shall we say, ludo, dominoes and all that sort of thing, things that you don't see so much today. Oh dear no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You don't remember particularly the little ones helping the bigger ones with anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
No, no, them that was to me quite the normal thing I suppose if - if we - putting us shoes on like, I mean, I can remember trying to get shoes onto the wrong foot. But these were things that - only slightly n
ow when you remember it, they didn't strike me as being funny at that time. The only thing is that - you'll - you'll never get your shoes on that way. I can remember Norah teaching me that, and - and teaching me to turn me own shoes. That type. Norah took
 charge of me but of course Hilda had taken charge of Norah, Frank had taken - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Were you expected to go to bed at a certain time in your schooldays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - yes. There was that little bit of difference between he older and the younger, the you
ng ones were put to bed much sooner. And I remember - usually at eight o'clock at night, it didn't matter, summer especially, we used to play in the recreation ground up Springbank. It's still there and me mother could come to the top of the street on Haz
el Street, and shout, and we could hear her on there and everybody that lived on Springbank could hear me mother's voice. And when she called - that meant come. And if we didn't come when she called well we got to know about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 That was your bedtime?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
And then - that was it. Well of course there was always - be - trying to evade getting washed and all that but we were always filthy, we used always to - to scrub before - before bedtime. And you can understand what that meant when there was - three
 - three of us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You three younger ones would go to bed earlier?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Yes, oh yes, we'd a regular time. Oh yes, and - and - and we used to have to be - even - even up to - I remember when - the first time I took the girl that became my wife, out - now
 what, I - I - I would be going up to eighteen. And the - and the - the night that I - I met her I took her - she lived over in Oakworth Road. And I come home and it was ten o'clock. And I got a lecture from me mother owing to the fact - she said, you've 
b
een out with a girl? I said, how do you know? She said, well I'd never come home at that time before. I never bothered to get dressed up. To that extent. And this was a start of - taking a pride in me own appearance in regard to that. And of course that w
a
s a lecture that I had to take her home - all this - and that was the first time that I ever remember answering me mother back. By saying that - I'd a - I'd a mile to walk after I'd taken her home. You see there were no buses. You see. They - they were - 
they were strict with us but they were very kind but they were strict and understanding.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 When you were very small do you remember who put you to bed, was it your mother or someone else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - me - me mother used to see that we went to bed, shall
 I put it that way. And - we used to go to bed, well I had me brother Wilfred, he used to sleep in the same bed as I. And if we didn't fight we sang. And usually we used to sing ourselves to sleep. Yes. But if it were a fighting match then me mother used 
t
o come up and fight the pair of us. And that was - that. So you can say that - that mother made sure that we were - in bed. But - we was really taught to go to bed ourselves. But she always - and - and in those days you know the gas were no - there was no
 - mantles or ought of that, they were just Bunsen burners you know, open flame. Now they used to come and make sure that - they were all right. Yes. That's a little thing that I'd forgotten, but I remember it quite plainly. And - and very dangerous too.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You shared the bed with your brother Wilfred?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
When you were at this house at Hazel Street, the back to back, where did everyone sleep, do you remember, you shared your bed with Wilfred, who else slept in that attic bedroom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well th
ere was Frank. He - he slept there and he had - he had a bed. Now he were much older than us and he used to come on - all of us you see, he were ten years older than - and if it was a cold night he used to come home and do a little bit of conjuring, he we
r
e - he - he was a - he - he'd developed this and - had he lived he would have been probably a modern David Nixon or something of that. Unfortunately he didn't. He used to do - all sorts of tricks. But had finish up by - probably having me out of bed to he
lp him. And then, as soon as I was out he'd get into where I had it warm you see. Then I had to get into his bed. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 These - there were boys' tricks that we used to get up to.}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you remember who actually slept in the attic bedroom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes, there was 
- there was Frank - there was David, when he was - when he was a baby, he eventually had to come up there, and there were Frank. He was the eldest. And Wilf and I. So the four boys - so the four boys eventually slept - but - as I say, we had to move from 
there over to Rawlings Street, back to Brier Street and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 In the attic bedroom you and Wilf had a double bed and Frank had his own single bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well it - no, he - he had but - no, it was a double bed because eventually you see it got so as that David.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 David slept with the eldest did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Yes. He - he got - it worked like that. Well it - it got so as that - we - we weren't particular who slept where really you know. Yes, if - if Frank - if Frank come home and - and he bought some chocolate
s or ought of that - I - I didn't mind sleeping with that. It isn't only that, Frank used to - when he started smoking - I used to pinch his ciggies. So of course I had to keep quiet. And cigarettes at that time was a - a penny for four Woodbines. Yes. An
d matches thrown in. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Do you remember the sleeping arrangements of the whole family, do you remember where the sisters slept when you were sleeping up in the attic?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - no, this is something that I really can't - you can say that - the big
 - in the - there was only one big - one big bedroom and it couldn't be all that big. And I think that this would be partitioned. And mother and father - and the - and the girls you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You won't remember how the three girls slept?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 No. No. You 
see, because Agnes - David - David was only a baby for quite - some time you see, he wouldn't - he wouldn't do much sleeping up in the attic in Hazel Street owing to him being a baby there, he'd be in a cot }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 somewhere}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 . Now these - these are things that - we
 didn't - and you must understand in those days that for boys to be going into the girls bedrooms and all that was - was quite wrong. Or at least we was brought up - that way. Didn't matter about the girls going up and making our beds and all that but we 
- yes. Oh yes, this was a - a thing that was - you know it seemed to be a pattern of life in those days. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You used to have your baths in the cellar?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes, we'd - you know, one of these big zinc - zinc baths and - and the copper that they used
 to boil the - clothes in. Have you ever seen one in the home. Used to fill it with water and put the fire underneath and that used to - that would be boiled.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 That would do for your bath water?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes, we - in that - and - they used to have to e
mpty it and then fill it up again while it was getting on. Oh yes, and - in those days Friday night they used to say well - Amami night, ladies hairdressing night and all that kind of thing. But that was a recognized bath night. Buy you can understand - b
oys like us when we'd been playing in the field and rolling about, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 bath night}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
 were more or less nearly every night. It - not - what you could call a - a scrubbing night, soaking night, but we used to have to - have to get in and - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you used to get the bath out most nights when you were so dirty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well - it used to hang on the wall and you could lift it down. Many a time if - if there were nobody to take charge well you know what it were, being boys, it were a skimping job anyway. But it - i
t was a must, we - but you could say in those days that a really a proper night when they had to put the copper on and the fire and - and fuel cost money and all that, you could say Friday night or Saturday night. That was the one night that was a must an
d no getting away from it. We couldn't evade it how we tried.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 On the other nights when you got very dirty how did you go on, if you needed a bath did you have it in cold water?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh - well - well no I wouldn't say that we had it in cold water reall
y, it was all to - to heat on a - either a big pan. 'Cos you know me mother had saucepans and all that you could nearly get in, you don't see them today. That was always on and then there was - he fire, the old fashioned fireplaces you know had like a sid
e - at the side of the fire. That was always full of water, so there was always hot water. Yes, and - and then -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So you'd have a bath more than once a week?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes, and - yes, and it was a case of this, that - this - the - the kitchenette on the top of the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 cellar head}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
 was big enough for one to have a wash down in like if you was - but of course it was a case this, that when someone went in we were kicked out. But of course I mean as soon as we were home from school, we was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 out}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 . We hadn't time for such as that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you remember when you had clean clothes to put on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Oh - well, yes, they - we had to change every week, there's no doubt about that, and sometimes - more often. But mind you, the clothes were cleaner than what they were good rea
lly. If you understand what I mean. The money wasn't there to be buying - what you could call clothes, that was - but - me mother made sure that we was clean, because in those days - you could go to school and you could come home filthy by - some people t
h
at you'd sat at side of. Used to - used to be a regular - a regular performance. Yes. But - you could say - if it came to a major change well that were like bath night, but there was many a time when you'd to - change underclothes for the simple reason th
at - we used to get filthy. Especially the boys, I can't speak so much for the girls. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 'Cos I don't know so much about the girls.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you remember where the family had their meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 There was the one room and we used to - sit round a big table you k
now, and it used to open out. And - we all sat down to the meal it - when it was possible. Me - me dad was the one what was missing mostly by the working away. And - it used to be - wholesome food - you know, what - what today would be called probably rou
g
h, but it was good, me mother used to bake what - bread every week or - tones and stones of bread and - make - puddings. I don't know what meat she'd get but it would probably be cheapest meat she could buy to feed the - to feed the flock and - and we had
 to have like bread with it, make these roly-poly puddings and suet puddings and - all that kind of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you ever remember having a meal in another room, other than this downstairs room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh no, no. No, no. There - there was really nowhere else where you could. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Where did your mother do her cooking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well - most of it - to my - I think that in the cellar - they had like a biggish gas - a gas oven. And I think most of it was done in the cellar by - because of the room. At the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 kitchenette}
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  - there wasn't - there was no room. It was mostly done - so it was hard work up - up and down the steps for her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 She did a lot of baking on the gas cooker in the cellar?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 She did all - oh yes. She did all her own baking and - and kneading
, used to; have, you know, big crocks. Great big - oh yes, make - make - if she made sweet cakes and that it used to be mixing and all. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Her cooking equipment was this gas cooker was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did she have a range as well in the living room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 The - the only range was one of the old fashioned - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 type}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 , you know, the - the bars at the front and - on like a kind of a thing, that could boil water and probably cook potatoes or boil a pan.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You didn't actually have an oven set in it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes, there was an oven at the side of the fireplace in which you could make Yorkshire puddings and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 She used that as well did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes. Yes, she used to use that. But if we were - for the extra cooking you might be a pan on the fire an
d the oven. There'd be the hot water which was only really fit for washing - utensils and washing yourself, you couldn't use it for to drink you know. And if there was any extras to do well it had to be done on the gas oven - and it used to be - as far as
 I'm aware it was in the cellar.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What time did you used to have breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Oh dear. Breakfast it used to be what - before we went to school. What time did we used to get to school, it would be before nine. We used to be leaving home round about h
alf past eight so we'd have breakfast - eight o'clock. And it would be what - bread - bread and - and a -probably some porridge. Used to have to be }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 porridge}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  and that for breakfast and that were about - about -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Bread and butter, did you ever have jam on it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Yes, it would be jam and all that but your - it was a case of this, me mother was a psychologist you see. There isn't much of that now, you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 didn\rquote t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  used much of that, and of course as soon as her back were turned you know we'd delve in and - and
 pinch it and all that, this was all part of something you learn when you grow older, to get you to eat it. Eat the bread and - fill yourself up. Well - yes. Now if you make a - make a - we'll say at dinner time, a suet pudding. Well we used to pull us fa
c
es at suet pudding and all that. Oh - now I used to like treacle on mine. And she used to say, now, you know it's all right you wanting this or this is expensive and there is not the money you can have - you can have a spoonful. Well, of course, as soon a
s her back was turned I used to - another. But - I realized after that this golden syrup and all that were treacle. It were cheapest she could buy, and of course all this were done - well, we thought we were doing something.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you remember who was present for breakfast when you were at school, were all the family there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well - well we - we had to go to school and you see your - in those days, you'd to put so many attendances in each year to qualify to go to work when you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 got}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  to be old enough. Oh yes. And - I - I can remember going into infants class and I can remember the name of the headmistress which was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 M}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 iss McKechnie, and a teacher was Miss Bushcombe and Miss Davis, I can remember them quite well. And me sister - used to take me and if I didn
't want to go well she used to make me go. And then of course when Wilf grew up and he had to go I had same performance with - yes, and we've had same performance with Agnes and David. In }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 
other}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  words we had - we - we - conducted each other.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 At breakfast time would most of the family be present to eat breakfast together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Oh yes, more or less, they were all together, until Hilda started to go to work. She went to work when she was twelve, so she went to work, I don't remember Hilda going to school much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 How did she go on for her breakfast, did she have it at work or did she have it before she left?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 No, there were no - no they had to have it at - before they went. Then they used to start at six o'clock you know. And come home -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Shed make her own breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well, me mother - me mother was at home, she used to make what - what breakfast there was. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 There was no such things as eggs and bacon and all that. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 If you had that were high day and holiday. Oh yes. But - Hilda - when she came 
home, they'd come home for about half an hour - at breakfast time, because I did the same when I went to work. We used to start about six, come home for half an hour, they came home at midday for - dinner. About an hour and finish about - going up to half
 past }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 five}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So they'd have a bit of breakfast before they went and then have another breakfast when you were having your more or less?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes, well - yes, probably when they went to work first thing they'd be lucky if they did get much before they w
ent, it'd be all - was bustle and scuttle to get to work to get back home yes, call it breakfast when they come back home.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you have anything special to eat on Sundays for breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well it - it was more or less - the same was breakfast tim
e. And - myself, I never have been - a breakfast eater. I am not now I hardly even now ever eat, but - but mealtimes, I've always been ready for me meals, and I even am today. And of course - Sunday well of course Sunday was Sunday. And it were - Yorkshir
e }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 pudding}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
 and meat, there'd be - I can remember mother like getting sirloin - this sirloin, it's the only piece in meat that I know. And I remember that. And - of course there was always plenty of potatoes and - and vegetables. But this was high day, this w
as Sunday and it was a - a day when we were all sat down together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 Did you have anything at all different for breakfast on Sunday?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well if - I don't think that we had so much different really from any other day at Sunday because - it used to be 
- we might have had a bit of toast or something like that but - but of course we had to go to Sunday school. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What did you call your midday meal, did you call it dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - we always referred to it as dinner.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What time would you have dinner during the time you were at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - six, seven - seven days a week was mostly the same and that was midday when we came home from school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 About quarter past twelve?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Round about that, you could say that because it - I went t
o Ingrow Council School which we all did and by the time that we'd got from Ingrow Council School over there you could say twenty minutes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What members of the family were present for dinner? Would those who were at work come home for dinner as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well - they was mostly all of us together. Even though - when they were working you see they used to come home from the mill about twelve. So far as I can remember. And we used to eat it together. Now this was of course - you can realize it - you don'
t realize it at the time, but you realize it when you get older and think back that this was done because it were far cheaper to have us all sat down together than to be - oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What did you usually eat and drink for your dinner?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well it - mostly tea. At one time there used to be cocoa, something liked cocoa. Tea. Or - coffee if anybody fancied it, but - mostly tea.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What would you have to eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well it was usually the usual you know. Vegetables or bit of cauliflower, cabbage, pe
as, potatoes. It be done various ways if we were lucky enough to have any - any meat going me mother probably - put some of the potatoes round the meat and - or - sometimes her might chip the potatoes and all but - everything was done what you could call 
on a very tight budget. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 But there was plenty of - of good wholesome food, there was plenty of it but it was all - all on a tight budget you know, there were nothing fancy. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you have anything different - you told me that on Sundays you always had roast beef and Yorkshire pudding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh that were a must on - aye, that was - oh that was - it was a must that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you have a pudding as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes, sometimes she'd make - rice puddings and - sago puddings and sometimes semolina. If - if 
the rice pudding were boiled in a pan we used to pull us faces a little bit, we used to - make no mistake, me mother were an artist, has know how to con us. Yes. There were none of us liked margarine. And she used to go down to the Maypole and get - marga
rine and they used to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 sell}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
 - a pound overweight with the margarine, before your time, but me mother used to get the man that used to do it to hit it with - they used to do it with pats - and - and on these they had - that made an impression that was butter.
 Me mother used to get him to hit this with the butter and we used to think it were butter, then of course we relished it. We all liked butter. Nobody liked margarine. It was same thing. And I don't - I can't tell difference today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What about the evening meal, did you call it tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well tea, of course tea - sometimes - when - if - at weekend we had to sit down we might have a little bit of something extra, I suppose it - depended how the budget balanced in - might have a - a little bit of boiled h
am or something a little - salmon, tinned salmon, weekend. But during week it used to be - tea - cake - me mother used to do most of her backing, of course all her baking. A bit of bread and jam. But - as far as I were concerned I couldn't get in fast eno
u
gh to get out, I were - and then - and the sooner I could get me tea and get out the better. And - and supper used to be - a similar - might - if she - might have made some soup and all - just depend what time we come in. And it just depend how good we'd 
been, if we'd been a bit awkward or obstreperous then we could go to bed - get nothing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 When was tea eaten, did you have tea when you got in more or less or did you all have it together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - more or less together when we could but - you see, 
when you're - and - well Frank like, he - when he started working of course he had - different times, he were much older than us and of course he came and went - many a time he'd probably have his meals out. Work - at his work you see, he was a joiner. An
d
 he started to earn good pay before long. But - Hilda, when she went to work, I remember her coming home and crying. Because she'd contribute to the family budget of half a crown for a full day - for a full week's work. I can remember that. And she was th
e first worker. So, of course, teatime - was for when she came home from the mill. Then when }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2171094\charrsid12214547 Norah}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
 went teatime for them when they came home from work. Us that were at school as I say we - unless it was a wet - day we would - we couldn't get out fast enough.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So you'd have your tea as soon as you got home from school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What time would that be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well about - four - half past four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So you'd have your about half past four?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 And those who were at work would have it when they got home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
When they got home from work which - was going up to six many a time, you see, used to - in the old days they used to work six 'til six and they had a half hour break for breakfast and an hour for what we called dinner, which
 of course is luncheon today, but it were dinnertime then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You usually had bread and butter and jam at teatime?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes, if we were lucky.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 On Sunday you sometimes had a bit of boiled ham?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh - or that type of thing. It might have been, what - for instance, they used to make like - this here - black }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 pudding}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 , }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 polony}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
 - type of haslett or something like that you know, this manufactured stuff. You can get thousands of different things today, salami, but you couldn't in those days. Maybe just that little bit of something that would tasty. That's about it, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did your mother ever make her own jam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes. Yes. If we could - you know, when the - when the - the fruit and that were cheap enough we could buy - go out and buy it. Yes, aye
 we could make it, I can remember helping to stir it in the big pans you know and bottling - putting it in jam jars.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did she ever bottle her own fruit or vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - yes, she used to do some like - when they used to pickle shallots from t
he garden and - there used to be red cabbage, they used - that used to be a favourite thing to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 She used to make pickles too?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Used to make piccalilli - and it used to be - you know, we used to hear more about the buying of the stuff and all tha
t of course, what we'd do when it were being made if we could pinch a spoonful well - we would do you see, just to make sure that it were - safe enough.;
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did she make any wine or any medicines for the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - no, it never went to making -
 making wine in that respect because I mean it were too costly but - they used to make such things linseed and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 liquorice}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
 and - and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 there\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
 this mixture for the time. You see, in the spring of the year and all that sort of thing and - brimstone and treacle if we had a sore throat and - vinegar and butter and sugar if we had a cough. Now these were the things that were - that used to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did she brew any beer for the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 No, I don't know, I can't remember her ever being - I fancy she thought there were enough - in a different }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 sphere}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  to - to make any. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did your father and mother grow their own vegetables and fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well he grew - in the garden he used to grow - the - vegetables, the usual garden vegetables, beans and - and that. Oh y
es, he was a good gardener. The fruit he - he grew would be }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 strawberries}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
. But more other kinds, I mean there was a - an allotment. Oh yes, he were a good gardener, he'd grow - swedes, carrots, potatoes, cabbages, pink ca-bage and white cabbage, beetroot. He - he grew - oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did they ever buy any fruit and vegetables?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 They bought - bought fruit. Yes, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 they\rquote d}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  buy - in the market, used to go in the market and - and of course - in the old days they used to many time at Saturday night they'd auctio
n these things. I can remember them - aye, cheaper and they'd go and buy them like. And - they used to be - used to buy sweets, they'd go down in these little stalls and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 they\rquote d}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  - they'd sell sweets or - you know and be at finish up with - all - a big bag for - for about sixpence, well sixpence were a lot of money but - fair enough. And that's how she used to do.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So they did buy fruit and vegetables from the market?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes. There was - there was never a glut. Oh no, but there -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did they ever buy any tinned or dried vegetables or fruit do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well - no - the most of anything that were bought in the tin line so far as I can remember would be the occasional tin of salmon or a tin of sardines which I never liked. And - and this of course was for high days and holidays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Sunday teas and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 If you were lucky, there - there was somebody }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 popping}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  in, you got some of that. But - that was - more or less - then of course there came to be the occasional tinned milk. 
That came onto the market you know like. And - an occasional tinned peas but - so far as I remember the most of anything in the tinned line was a tine like an occasional tin of salmon or - that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did they keep any livestock for the family, hens or pigs or goats?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well - me dad - for a few year, more or less after he retired, he had a - a - a hen run which as I say is on the roadside even today but of course - he only kept it going for so many years, then of course it got - past him. Then -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 This would }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 be}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  after 1919 would it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes, I - yes, I think it would be. That - when he came to be - yes, it'd be after that because -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you remember him ever keeping hens before 1919?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 No. I can't remember him keeping hens any before he retired
. Well, I'm saying before he retired. He started just before he retired. But - but of course we was getting on towards the first world war at this particular time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 How many times a week did you eat meat, do you remember?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh - I wouldn't like to say. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 I wouldn't like to say. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 It weren't so often as all that because I mean - the money wasn't there to buy it. You could say that - what - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 you\rquote d}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  - we - we'd happen have a little - on Saturday. There's certainly be some on the Sunday and I - and I - I fan
cy the rest'd be what was left to make up into soups and that type of thing. No, I wouldn't say that meat, there was what you could call a really a - a thing that was - evident because - money just weren't there to buy it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you ever buy potted meat or tripe or sausages or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Aye. Now - there was times - yes, there were times when - what was referred to as offal in those days, tripe, yes, me mother used to get - tripe and onions and make a soup - make a - a kind of a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 sauce}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 , all mix up together. It were lovely, and - and I could eat some of that now if it were here. Yes, it was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Tripe and onions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes. And - and it was very palatable and there's no doubt that it was filling and believe me we wanted some filling.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you ever have sausages during the week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well I wouldn't - I cannot - no, I can't remember -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you ever get some extra meat such as a rabbit from poaching?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Poaching? Well - I know - that - at one time in those days and I'm going back n
ow when I was a youngster, I remember that one or two of me father's friends - that used to go round in the - the woodland and they might have caught a - a rabbit or two. Yes, it's quite possible that me dad might have brought home an occasional rabbit. T
hat - what we call would have been one. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So it was fairly infrequent?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Oh it - yes, it - this were a high day and a holiday if one of these rolled up and we - we were told - how this came about. I mean - when it were there this were something 
that we looked forward to, oh this was a treat, yes. But - it's only in the later years when you come to think back and I got to know the run of other things and learnt how to do a bit of poaching myself when I went up into the Peak District. Oh yes. That
 I realized it, not at that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you remember seeing your mother having less }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 food}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  so that the family could have more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - I daresay that that did take place. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 
We were too young to notice - or probably a little too selfish to notice that me mother didn't have as much as she ought to have done - but - I do believe that that was quite right, not only in our family but in many, many families. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 The parents went short to let the children have it. There's no doubt about that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What about your father, did he usually have more than the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well, I wouldn't say that he had more but I do think this you see, let's be fair about this, that when me dad was working and - and moving about from one part to another is expensive and then - in th
ose days, there would no doubt be many a time when there would be tips that he would get from some of the eminent people. That he would be able to go out and probably buy himself a - a meal, at any time or something to eat. When he was working - just to g
i
ve an illustration, in the old days, and this'll be interesting to your husband, they used to have a - a place to fill hot water bottles you know. So that they could - let the first class passengers to have these to put to their feet to keep their feet wa
rm. In fact they charge them a shilling. Yes. Now - a first class passenger in those days, to have something to keep his feet warm, was quite prepared to pay a shilling and probably give another. And I can remember the - the doges they used to get up to.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So your father would make the old shilling?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
He would make an old shilling or two which would supplement me mother's budget when he eventually come home. And probably at that time that would - well, a little bit of extra food would come in - by the tips that the got because - in those days, }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 believe}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  me, it - it was so. Sir James Ellison Haggas, Sir John Clough and all those }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 travelled}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  by train. Now if you opened the door for these people - they'd - they'd give something, if it - if it was - what - six
pence, not sixpence was a lot of money. Yes, I can remember them things being told.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Were you allowed to talk during meals or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 We weren't. No. We were told - to put it in the Yorkshire }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 vernacular}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 , to let us jock stop of mouths. Yes. Then we s
at - when we were there - there was a saying in those days that children had to be seen and not heard. And we could well do with some of it today. And if we opened us mouth when we shouldn't do me mother had a came and it - and that was it on the top of t
he knuckles. Oh yes, they - we - we was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 disinclined}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
, not - we wasn't - we wasn't oppressed. No, we were - but we had to do as we was told, obviously.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Could }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2171094\charrsid12214547 you}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
 choose what you wanted to eat from what was cooked or did you have to eat a bit of everything that your mother made?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well - I do have a - remember being made to eat anything that I didn't want. I think me mother made as much of - of the food that she could that we all liked owning to economic circumstances we had to do. But if we didn't lik
e it we was never made - it eat it. And we was never told that, if you don't eat that you can't have another certain thing, we was never told that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What was their attitude if you did leave something uneaten on your plate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - if we left anyt
hing - she was under the impression that we weren't so well. For the simple reason that we all had good appetites and we was always ready and if there were any chance of a second helping we were there to take it. But - if we did leave anything then you wa
nted to know why we didn't really want it and you could say that it was because - we hadn't - weren't just up to the mark.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 If there was something on the table you wanted like the salt could you ask someone to pass it to you or did you have to wait unti
l it was offered to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
No. If - when we sat down at the table - things were there. Now, we sat down to a meal to eat and to - we was growing children and we was expected to eat. If we wanted anything we wasn't allowed to reach over. We had to ask. 
If I wanted the salt, will you pass me the salt please, can I have the - yes, I wasn't allowed to reach over. No, we - we had to ask.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Could you ask for a second helping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes. Yes. And a third if it was there. If we wanted it. But mind you - when
 we come to weigh it up like, on the money that came in and seven mouths to feed and nine if me mother and father at home, there was never what you could call a big surplus. But if it was there we could have it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Were you expected to hold your knife and fork in a certain way and sit in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
We had to sit and we'd to sit straight and I used to sit on a stood and I sit on it today if I can. Yes, there - there weren't enough chairs to go round. And when we was younger - we used to have to s
tand. You see, there were no chairs to sit down. When we were smaller we could just reach over the table, the - the youngest would stand. Then when we got that big enough. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 
You see, a baby had one of these high chairs, but I've stood at the table to eat me meal and not once but many, many times, 'til I got - big - bit older and -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What about the knife and fork?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Oh yes. We was taught to use a knife because you see, me dad, he'd been brought up in service and everything had to be - in service had to 
be that way, and he used to - teach us the way to set the knife and fork out the spoons and all that, as though we was going to have an elaborate meal, probably what we - I suppose it'd been better off - but we was - yes, we was taught, and in - in those 
d
ays although me dad was left handed none of us had been left handed. But you had to use your right hand when you could, and your left hand. Of course the left hand knife and fork came natural. Because we was taught that. But even me dad used to write - an
d he was a beautiful writer - but he wrote with his right hand. They used to teach to do that, but today they don't stop them. But they stopped them in those days.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Could you bring toys or a book to the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 At mealtime? Oh at - at mealtime it 
was mealtime. And - and no - once the table was cleared then that was put - for us to - play. Each according to - his likes and sis likes, or whatever toys we had, believe me we hadn't many.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 But you weren't allowed to at mealtimes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Mealtimes were mealtimes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 When could you leave the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
When we asked, we used to - when we'd finished - and - and we didn't use go - we didn't used to get the leave the table until everybody had finished. We used to have to sit there - we weren't allowed 
to talk. When the meal were finished if we were lucky enough to have a drink of tea afterwards, you know, like a drink of tea which seemed to be a custom and I love a cup of tea at any time, then we could - discuss - after, but not during the meal hen we'
re eating, when we're having a cup of tea, but of course in those days, we - we didn't really have time to bother, we - soon as meal were - we wanted to be off. We were either going to school or -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did all the family sit at the table for the meal, you said that some had to stand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - yes, in other words - we were too little, no, there'd be no chairs to go round anyway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you all actually go to the table for the meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes. Oh yes, yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you always have the same places at table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
We had our original places and that were mine and that was Norah's and that was - and this was - not - really a ritual, shall I say it just grew on the family, you see, you fit in and that was it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So you had your own particular places?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
We'd - we'd us own places which was quite automatic, it wasn't - if I went and sat down at the table and I was on me own - then it wouldn't matter, but if - we'll say that somebody came in I'd automatically go to my own place. Nine - nine times
 out of ten you sit in hour place where you're accustomed to sitting. I - I do in me own place even now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
How was the meal served and by whom, did your mother put all the food out on the plates and give you the plates or did she put all the food in tureens on the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well - in those days me mother used to serve it up but there - the - the vegetables was put in tureens and me dad, when he was at home, if there was any meat cut, he used to cut and carve the meat. I think this was part of the job 
that he used to do when he was in service and he - he could cut, in other words, I daresay he could make a little go a long way. To put it - to put it truly, but he - I can remember him cutting the meat, but me mother used to be - be - server, she used to
 serve it out and - and from tureen probably, as we got older we might have helped ourselves, but as I told you, before the - the first world war well of course it was served for us. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What order were you served in, was there any special order?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 
Not - no, not particularly, I think it was a case of - the nearest or farthest - no, I wouldn't say there was any really particular - order or ought of that, except that the ninety-per cent of the time it'd be me mother'd be the last, you can bet your li
fe on that.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Where did your younger brothers and sisters sit before they could feed themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well - we had one of them - high back - you know, there used to be a high back chair you could - higher them and lower them. And they had a - a tray. 
I can remember sitting in that. See you can tell how far back I can - yes, and we used - used to feed them there, they used to sit - and I was brought up near to the table to me mother. Or to me elder sister so that they could be fed in that respect. Oh y
es.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Who fed them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well - me mother mostly fed - fed 'em, but Norah and Hilda, they weren't above feeding them. And if I - if I was handy and they were wanting - shall we say like - like milk pudding or ought of that - I might feed 'em but if I co
uld get out of it I - that's right. Because it - it wasn't a boys job. No, in those days, if - if you can understand my meaning, and to me I think it - it was been all wrong. A boy wasn't supposed to bake, he wasn't supposed to wash up, he wasn't supposed
 to do - he wasn't supposed to make beds, all wrong. It were a girls job.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 They used to sit in a high chair, do you know how old they would be when they were able to come to the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - no - no. You see, in those days - when they came it - 
it was when they could reach, they didn't come really 'til they could reach to help themselves, to feed themselves. Three - three years old. They - they used to - little boys used to wear little frocks and petticoats 'til they were about two year old you 
k
now, and you don't hear - you don't hear it today, they used to say, well I'm going to - what they call a little boy - they're going to britch him, put him in trousers. You don't hear that today. Oh yes, and - he used to have - used to have a curly hair, 
of course - oh dear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 This lady who used to come and help your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 That Mrs Taft.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did she used to have her meal with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 She - oh yes. Yes. She - she'd sit down and have her meal at that particular time and probably - that would be
 the day when me mother and her would have a meal probably on their own. It's very - I remember her coming in and - she seemed to be there nearly all day because it - believe me it was terrible the washing. Used to have two big tubs and copper going and o
h
 dear oh dear. And they used to use pushers and all that. I have helped - used them. Oh yes,; and I've even - turned a mangle you know, there used to be big mangles. Yes, she did used to have a meal and I think this was all part of the payment that the - 
that there was allocated to - well wash - called the washerwoman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Was your mother an easy person to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Easy? Oh yes, she was a - she was a lovely woman was me mother, although I say it myself. Yes, she was - she was - what I call an intelli
gent woman to talk to and she - she could converse and - yes, I - I - I - as far as I - I think she was very easy to get on with.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did she show affection?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes. She - she had a - an affection that wasn't - shall I say sloppy. No, she weren't - she
 - she was an affectionate - and affectionate woman and - and she showed it - mostly as a mother to her family. I don't know the - any affection that existed between me mother and father, I mean, I was too young to know about - I suppose there'd be the sa
me affection between man and wife as there was between me and - my own wife. And - and I believe at the bottom of it, probably I have a little of me mother's affectionate nature. And yet - none of us }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 wore}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  his heart on our sleeves, we was brought up to - keep us moans and us groans to ourselves.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You said she wasn't sloppy - you mean she didn't demonstrate her affection for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 No, no, no, no. No. If - if you - if you wanted comfort then she'd comfort it in a mother - motherly way. You know, and -
 show that bit of affection, but there was none of this - well - I don't know really how to term it - falling all over you, there was none of that, she was very affectionate though, and she - no doubt she loved her family as we loved us mother and us fath
er.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 If you had any worries could you share them with her or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Yes. Yes, you could share - in fact, you were expected if you'd any troubles, you were - as I say, we - we hadn't to wear us heart on our sleeve but - me mother could read us nearly
 like a book. Probably better than we knew ourselves and she could tell if there was something worrying or - and if there was any problem then - they'd - she'd try and shoulder 'em and we could talk - I could talk to me mother far better than probably I c
ould to me dad.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Would you say your father was quite an easy person to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Me father was a - a - a - a very - yes, he was a talker, he was easy to talk to. I - I wouldn't say that - he was affectionate in a - it's rather hard to find a word t
o suit a man, but he used to take me to football matches and - loved to take me to these concerts you know that used to be the music hall, the singers, I used to love that and I - he used to take me to them. I don't recollect him taking anyone else. And I
 
can remember him taking me to see one of the first animated pictures that was in Keighley, at the Mechanics Institute and - I could talk to him, but I wouldn't say that I would talk to him about - what shall we way - really personal problems. I remember s
a
ying to him, when I was going out, I was out of work and he said, by gum, you're dressed up? I said, yes, I'm going to meet me best girl tonight. He said, eeh I thought you'd more lamp in your lamp than that? Aye, I said, it flickered and it's gone out. A
nd I think them are about the only things that I ever remember - has stuck in mind and discussing any -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What - if you had any worries could you share them with your father or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - well the worries that - were - at that time, were more or l
ess, what shall we say, only childish worries in - in regard to - what could we do, what couldn't we do and the only thing that was impressed upon me in regard to talking about anything was, I would have to decide to go learn a trade. This, at that time s
e
emed to be the one main thing in everybody's life. You had to learn to have a trade. And I couldn't have cared less what I was going to do. So when it came to talking, I wanted to go on the railway, he wouldn't entertain it owing to the wages being low an
d of course that was that. That's as far as any discussion and worries that I had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 How did your parents expect you to behave towards them?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - I don't know what they expected - what - it really boils down to that - myself - I thought a lot ab
out my parents and - and so it was quite a natural feeling that - that what they said went, was law, and of course must have been right. That's as far as I would like to say in that respect, I mean, I thought a lot of me parents and I - I'm under the impr
ession they thought a lot about me. And - that's as far as it really - struck me at that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did your parents bring you up to behave towards your brothers and sisters in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well we are - never to forget that I had sisters. And we ha
d to treat all girls, woman, with a respect that - we always - me own sisters and me mother. Now that was brought up from childhood right the way throughout our lives and we'd never to forget it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 And how about your brothers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well about this brot
her, well of course we had to be boys - and - and we'd to act like boys and we'd to be honest and the one thing it was that we had not to lie. We was always brought up to remember that when you started to lie you had to have long memories. So therefore we
 wasn't - if we was caught out in a lie then we got the thick end of the stick - not the thin end.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What would they say if another child hit you, would they say you should hit them back or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - if - if we came home and say I had a couple of
 black eyes, which I many a time did have - what had I done in the first place. And - if we'd been fighting there was two sides to each question. And it was a case of stand on your own feet. And - and if there was anything wrong, if I'd done wrong, then I
 
got another pasting on top of what I'd already had. But - we - we weren't - we weren't stopped from being boys and - if we - if we did have a - a rough house, well, we were allowed to have a rough house, but if it got out of hand, then believe me mother c
ould - yes, she could put us straight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What kind of people do you think your parents hoped you would grow up to be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well I - I don't think they would have wanted me to be really any different to - to what I've really developed, knowing as things 
are. But at that particular time I wouldn't know. Now, I was rather keen on - drawing, sketching, cartooning I loved to do that, I spent hours drawing where other children would do others I spent a - I was encouraged to do that. Unfortunately there wasn't
 
the money there to encourage me to go out to build up on it. So - I had to go into the mill, and I went when I was twelve. I went to the night school at the Keighley Mechanics - for four - five year. Four nights a week, yes. And one of them was with a vie
w
 to being a draughtsman in an engineering firm - other was - to take up a kind of woodwork, and I took up woodcarving instead of woodwork which was an all - a mistake. And - I took, like a kind of mathematics to go with - and I did very well taking it all
 by and large, but there was all the wrong - wrong subjects really.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You felt they didn't help you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well they haven't helped me over the years. Who wants woodcarving today? No one. If I come to do any woodwork today it finishes up as firewood. An
d I mean mathematics, well, I get in the ordinary sense. And I went to Darling and Sellers in 1914 - 1914 and I became an apprentice turner - then severed me time 'til 1921. Unfortunately after 1918 there became the slump. And - three days a week, three d
ays a fortnight, finally out of work. No work then 'til 1922 when I came on the railway and loved every minute of it from that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You can't remember your parents discussing what they'd like you all to become?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 No. They just - no, they wanted me
 to please myself. I did have an opportunity put to me to go to be taught cartooning with a - a teacher called Mr Winscolme at the Wesley Place evening classes. But unfortunately I'd started as an engineer at Darling and Sellers and I thought I was going 
t
o be an engineer and I would never have made an engineer from that day to this. 'Cos I never really wanted to study it. And - the subsequent events of me life made me a fatalist and I finished up on the railway where I wanted to start as a lad. And - and 
as I say, from that day to that I studied railways and made it a hobby and made it a - enjoyable work and I loved every minute of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did your parents bring you up to consider certain things important in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes, up to a point. The first thing 
was that we'd to be honest with ourselves and everybody else. There was a - the possibility of a rainy day and - not to waste - shall I say, food or anything that - could be saved. Apart from that I mean when it came to the money side of it, well here was
 no money, so we couldn't waste it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What did they think of swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Swearing? Well - to me I can never remember hearing me mother swear, I can remember hearing me dad occasionally swearing, and it always sounded bad. And - we aren't have been heard to swear but - let me }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 be}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  fair, as a lad I knew all the words and all the answers and of course - I }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 daren\rquote t}
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  - I daren't have used it at home. None of the family dare either, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 When grown up were talking were you allowed to join in?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well it
 all depends on - on what was being discussed. Now for a start - sex was never discussed as it is today. Books was never withheld from us, the papers was always available. I was encouraged to read, it didn't matter what. We'd read - we'd to think for ours
e
lves. We were - sent to the Sunday school. We were sent to the - temperance hall and to these - but I think most of it were to get us out of the way rather that - any teaching. But - when it come to discussing, oh yes, if we was to talk with - with - but 
it was a case of you speak when you're spoken to and not - not before. That was a - a - seemed to be - the - the times. Yes, we could discuss things but you weren't - encouraged to talk about a lot of things that they are today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 If you did something that your parents disapproved of what would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
If they were cross? Well - it just depends what it were. If - there was something that we'd done when we was children we were sent to bed. And that was it. Now - but we was never sent to bed without -
 anything to eat or to drink. We was never debarred that. If I did something wrong - then I got - a good hiding. Not only from me mother but from me father. Very seldom from me father. But from me mother. And we always dealt the same - there was no fish o
f one and flesh of other. Now we used to play football and cricket. Accidents happen, accidents are - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 forgivable}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
. We'd break somebody's window. Now - if we went home and told that we had broken the window, we was helped to pay for it. If we didn't tell we'd
 broke the window we got a good hiding and made to pay for the window out of what bit of spending money - which meant that we had then to go do little jobs for people to get hold of a copper or two to pay our way, so we - we was - strictly brought up in t
hat respect.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You said sometimes your mother would smack you if you'd don something wrong?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Aye, and she did smack us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 How often would this happen do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - not really - not really a lot, for the simple reason that - as I say,
 once you - once you've been punished for a thing you're not going to seek it again. And I still believe that today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So not very often?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well no - no more probably than any ordinary child.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did your father ever smack you for anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 I
 can't really remember him - smacking me to any - any degree at all because for the simple reason he didn't spend as much time at home as a normal parent would. But he - had other ways of punishing us by making us probably go down and do a bit of gardenin
g which I hated. He had that one way and that was - that was worse. You - I'm going to dig some potatoes up, you're going down to help me. You see. I }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11946338\charrsid12214547 wouldn\rquote t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 have - refused because I mean I would - but - no, I - I - there are very}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 ,}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  very few occasions that I can remember ever being smacked by my dad but - the few was there. Oh yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Can you remember any particular occasion when you were punished either by being sent to bed or being smacked or being made to work in the garden?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 We-l - no, no, I - it
's vague in my mind that probably some childish things, I might have taken something belonging to - me brother or - or I might even have taken it off someone or I might have caused a bit of bother on one thing, no, I can't - I can't remember the reason, t
h
ey why and the wherefore, but I do remember being sent to bed. And I hated it because I mean - when you're sent to bed at six and seven year old you knew the things that you could be playing. Playing games you see. No, I wouldn't like to say that - I coul
d
 - I war rather more - I've always been - one that could - be a loner and - and - and on my own. But the same if there were anybody else had ought I wanted I wasn't above going and borrowing it off 'em. Like any other child you see and of course you took 
it off a - another child, well that's wrong, then you could be punished and that were it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you remember how you felt about being punished.?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Felt? Resenting it, oh yes, I - oh yes, I resented it, I was - I was quite resentful for quite some time
 and - and thought a lot about it but I took jolly good caf\'e9
 that - I weren't going to lay myself open. Oh no, no, but I can remember - that kind of thing and I do believe that today - the resentment for such things would probably be just a little bit predominant even today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Would you say that you received the ideas you had about how to behave from both your parents or did one play a more important part than the other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well I - I think me mother was the guiding factor because she had us there all
 the time. I aren't going to say that there wasn't any collusion between them because - there would be, but you can understand - like me dad being away twelve hours a day and many time we didn't see him and when he came up well we made a fuss of him and h
e - he used to take us and if he had a - a bit of time off he'd }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 take}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
 us out on to the moors, and he was quite a young man when he was getting - older, he were - he could play with us, and talk to us, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 When you had a birthday would it be different from any other day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - not really that you'd notice }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 it}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  but except that you might have got some - what - a few sweets or - a little toy I mean, a sixpenny toy at that time would - would be worth - why it would be worth the world. No, there was noth
ing really, you mean, in the way of parties or ought of that. No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You'd have some little present would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well if it was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2171094\charrsid12214547 it}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  would be something more useful like handkerchief or new tie probably and a pair of shoes or a pair of socks. Some childish thing probably but nothing that'd make it a lasting memory.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 didn\rquote t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  remember having anything special to eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 No, no, no, no, it - the point is this that when it came round and there were seven birthdays to consider they couldn't make fis
h of one and flesh of another.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you have any guests, any little friends in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well - not so as it sticks in my mind. If I did it was - only the - the boys that I went mates with, I knew - kind of went two - two or three of us, they might have c
ame in for tea but it isn't so - not to that extent, it wasn't really anything to get excited about.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 There wasn't a fuss made of birthdays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 No, and to be quite candid I've never really been one - that - been a party boy, I never really - I could
 probably have sulked before had one of them, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Can you remember anything you did with mother and father together on Christmas Day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - nothing no more than it being Christmas Day. There was always a - you know, like the usual Christmas pa
rty at that time. You played your games, you'd have a - a little extra - as you got older there would be games to play, there was no tele, no - no wireless, no - no }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 gramophones}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  or ought of that, you made your own fun. Oh yes, we had some nice Christmas Day
s, we had extra meals, extra dinners. Toys. That wouldn't cost the earth but to us meant such a lot. Oh yes, such a lot to us as we grow older. And of course the bigger ones as they grow older they played - and - enjoyed it with us smaller ones and - Chri
stmas was Christmas, and we made it Christmas, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you have any musical instruments in the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 We'd none at all. None at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did any of you play a musical instrument at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 No. There was nothing, we had nothing. Norah and -
 well the girls, they could sing. They'd good voices. David, he even took lessons to go singing. Yes, but as for instruments either - as I say there was neither }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 gramophone}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  nor radio, tele, no nothing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What about a piano?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 No piano. No. There was nothing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you ever all sing together at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Sing? Yes, I should - I should imagine by our standard it would be terrible. But we often used to sing. Oh yes, we - we'd have sing - Norah and - and - the girls had quite tolerable voices, they 
could sing. And me mother, I - I think she was a lovely singer, she often used to sing to me. I can remember sit - so far back as a child, her singing songs to me - some of those I can remember today, I wish I knew the titles of those. I do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did your parents play any games with you at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Oh aye. Yes. Yes. And in - in the old days you know we used to play - the games that all young people played, postman's knock and - all the usual Christmas games and paper games you know. I've forgotten the names of them now. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Were there books in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Books? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 
Oh yes, we'd - books when - when we could come and as soon as ever they got to be able to join same as a library or ought of that they'd bet library - and there'd be - we could read 
- I used to get the - the Union Jack and Sexton Blakes and all that type of thing. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 And at the time there was the comic papers, Chips, Comic Cuts, Magnet. They all used to come in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Were there any books at home that were your own, either your parents or yours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well - well I wouldn't - I wouldn't say that, I had books that we got presented with you know, like - some Sunday school, Midshipman This and - oh titles that I've forgotten - Tom Brown's schooldays and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So they'd be mainly }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 children\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  books that you'd have at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh - well at one time, Uncle Tom's Cabin and all that sort of thing. Of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you get any newspapers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes, of course the - the main - always the main paper was of course the Keighley News, no home was
 complete without the Keighley News. And then - I wouldn't like to say what the Sunday papers was in this day and age, they were just - a Sunday papers or - I wouldn't like to say, they were there to read if we wanted. Me dad used to try and get us intere
s
ted in - in - politics. But we - we were too young to - worry and if there was any major speeches he'd try and - as we grew older and older he used to try and get us - shall we say, involved. But we hadn't time. No, I wouldn't - I wouldn't like to say wha
t the papers was at that time, I wouldn't know. Probably the News of the World or some paper like that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 But you didn't }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 get}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  a daily paper?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well if - if there was a daily paper coming you could bet that it would be one that me dad'd get out, say L
eeds Mercury or - at that time - something like that. No, I don't recollect that we ever - oh yes - in the later days they used to be the Yorkshire Evening News, there used to be the Evening News, there used to be a boy, he's still living, he used to brin
g
 it. But that were as we was getting a little bit older. I remember that, the Evening News, the Yorkshire Evening News. That used to come. That were - towards the back end of - growing up, as far as I remember I'd be getting up - going up to ten I should 
imagine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you get any magazines at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Me mother used to get one, I think it were called }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 Woman\rquote s}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  Weekly. She used to get that and it used to have a - a little strip in, something about a parrot and I can remember I always wanted to look at th
at, I used to watch that, that were my page, that was all I was interested in, as a child.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You said you used to get some children's comics as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes, we'd comics - Chips, Comic Cuts, the Magnet -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you all get your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh no,
 no, there were - ewe - we shared - we shared that, I mean, we all looked at them. There was no - this is yours, this is mine. Oh no, they was there. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you remember a funeral in the family in this period before 1919?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 A funeral? No - not to know - anything about it except that I can remember me grandma Page dying and being buried.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you remember what happened?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 But - no. All that I do know is that everybody had to have - something black if you could, they'd to dress in black. It w
ere quite a miserable occasion, I don't remember much of it. They had - they have black edge }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 cards,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  black }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 edges}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
 on the - on - writing paper and that you know like and they're - and they're really miserable for a couple of days or something like that. I remember -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you go to the funeral?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 I DON'T think so. I - I - it's very vague, very vague in my mind.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You've no recollection of any other funerals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 The only recollection which I have which would probably interest men was - and I didn'
t go, I don't think much about it, be about 1906 and that were when Harry Myers, the Keighley full back died, he - he was kick - he broke his neck on the football field and he was - and international full back for Keighley Rugby League Club, it was Rugby 
Union at that time, and he was buried and I can remember me dad being very, very miserable about it all, but I was too young - to understand. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 But that is something that I can remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Would you remember who attended your grandma's funeral or would you be too young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well - yes, of course naturally me mother and me dad, they would go. If there were anyone else I wouldn't know. Neither would I know who - who was involved in its at all, I wouldn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Were you taken out visiting neighbours or friends or relations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 
Well - we - we was taken - we was taken to see relatives now obviously, me mother coming from Shrimpling in - in Suffolk and me dad coming from Brinklow in Warwickshire, he had sisters there, me had mother had relatives there and - w
e used to go and of course me father being a railway man he could get passes for - the railway to take us and so we used to - us to take us there for holiday once a year. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
And occasionally take - probably take us to - an outing like probably to Liverpool to see the boats or - or that. We - these were free - these were free - free passes to take - and he could take the family, otherwise - if it }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 hadn\rquote t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  have been I doubt whether we'd have got anywhere.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You didn't have any neighbours, friends or relations who lived in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 Keighley
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 , that you used to go and visit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Oh I had - yes, I had - what we called mates, I had - several, there was about seven of - boys all went together. As we grew up and we all friends, we used to visit each others houses and as we started, you know, getting involved with the }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 girls}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  we used to go and meet and take 'em to each other's houses. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 When you were a small boy do you remember your mother and father taking to you to anyone's house, such as a friend of theirs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes
. I can remember - no, no, but I can remember them taking me to an old lady, they called her Hibbitt and she lived up Station Road I think it was at Oakworth, and she used to make this lace on a pillow. And I used to sit and watch her make these with thes
e - you see it on the telly a few weeks back, and making - making the lace. Used to take us to see that. I used to go and see them. But -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 She was a friend of theirs was she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 She was a friend of - and I think like probably - she was an old lady, 
probably her husband, I don't remember him, he might have been dead, would of course be some of me dad's through railway working. Yes. I can remember her making the lace.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You didn't have any very regular visits to people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 No, no. No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 This was just an odd visit you made to this lady?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 It - there were - high days and holidays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 With whom did you go - both parents - when you visited this lady at Oakworth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - sometimes, it just depends you see, to go to Oakworth it weren't far, probably if me dad took us me mother was glad to see ba}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 c}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 k of us. And I think -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 w}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 ell I think it was more to get us out while - you see, as the girls were growing up probably they did more housework and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Were you ever taken shopping with your parents? Or with your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well, yes, we used to go - shopping, but it were under protest.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You didn't like it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 But you did have to go occasionally?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Sometimes we used to have to go.
