, lovely little country places and - we'd probably go chasing rabbits and never catch any but - you know, spend it that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 It would be a complete change for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes. Oh yes, and you'd go visiting, there were several aunts and uncle you'd go, 
well of course they used to make their own wines and - they had their orchards and of course we - had lots of things that we would never get at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Could you tell me about how you spent your Saturdays in those days, what you would do on A Saturday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well in - as a youngster - there was really nothing, it was a case of - of playing - playing about in the recreation fields but then when they started with the pictures - then you could go to pictures for about a penny.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Would that be Saturday afternoon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Saturday afternoon and one of the people that had it was at - where the Bingo hall is in Cavendish Street. And they called him Harry Plant and he used to give these one - picture shows and all that sort of thing a penny, and if we - and if w
e got obstreperous he used to give us sticks of rock to get us out, so that we could all come home quietly. There was a picture house up Russell Street Market Street. And - and it - you know - yes, and of course - you know, it was Charlie Chaplin and Bust
er Keaton and all that kind of thing. Silent pictures you know and somebody playing the piano. Oh they were good, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What did you used to do on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Sunday we had to be on our best behaviour, it was Sunday school at morning, Sunday school
 at afternoon - and - we'd happen go for walks, this would be probably when the parents would take us for a walk. Or if we was in it was play games. Ludo. All that kind of thing. We wasn't allowed to play out in the street nor no kicking a ball about, you
 didn't - no, you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 did not}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  - no, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you have any different clothes on a Sunday, you didn't wear clogs on a Sunday, you wore your shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 We wore our shoes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you have special clothes for Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 We had a Sunday suit, had 
a Sunday suit, but don't ask me what colour they were, I - I wouldn't know, and if you asked me where they were came from or }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 how}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  we got them I wouldn't know but we had a Sunday suit. And I suppose they - they was bought - the hard way. We all had Sunday suits and we daren't - we daren't go - oh - oh we }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 daren\rquote t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
' do anything - in them, we had to be very careful what we did. And we used to put aprons - an apron, wear aprons when we were in the house, oh yes, to keep 'em clean. And if we wanted to do anything -
 like - see if we'd a cellar and we were going to play in the cellar when the - as same as us mates come we'd get in the cellar and play. Well - no Sunday suit, we'd to get into us old clothes to - oh yes, yes. The Sunday suit were your Sunday suit. And t
hat was an end to it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you play games on a Sunday, were you allowed to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh - not outdoors, you couldn't - we couldn't - oh if you played in - inside that was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 all right}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 , but - at that time they were limited you know. If you played games, I don'
t know if you've ever seen them play - leap - what we call leap frog and - and these here when you jump on one another's backs and see how many can get - you don't see it today but - these were games that we played and if we played - because it was a wet 
Sunday, it'd probably be either in the cellar - in our cellar or probably one of my mates' cellars or - we used to take it in us turns I expect, and that was it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did your parents think it wrong to work or play on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well, oh I wouldn't say
 that about working for the simple reason that me dad had to work on Sundays you see, his work took him on Sundays. Me mother had to work all day preparing food and that, there was no objections to working Sunday. But they - they wouldn't let us go out an
d play like football or with a ball or cricket or anything of that on a Sunday.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did your parents attend a place of worship or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well me mother went to St Johns. I don't recollect me dad going to much, I don't ever he had time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Is St Johns a Church of England church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 That's the one just here, yes, Church of England. Oh yes, St }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 Johns}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 . And she used to go to Bible class and women's guild, women's meetings and to the church. And I've gone, in the younger days, I used to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 go}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  often go to the church with her and I used to love to hear them - hear them singing, the singing of the hymns and that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 But you don't remember your father attending church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 I can't say that I remember me dad going.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 How often would your mother go to church do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well - I - I've a job to remember but she did used to go fairly frequently and she used to - in the latter days she went - once a week to the like - same as the mother's guild or something of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Was that during the week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
That was during the week. But at Sunday she might - I - I - I remember they used to go sometimes at morning. To the morning service. And evening service. If she went to morning service I doubt whether she'd go to evening service. And evening service'd be 
when she'd finished all the - household }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 chores}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you ever go to church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Yes, I went - I used to go morning and many a time at evening. But - yes, to the church service. But - but - but before that like I used to have to go to the Sunday school, it used to be Sunday school at morning, Sunday school at afternoon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 But you didn't go to church at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh no, I - we weren't considered like really old enough to understand what it was but as soon as we got to be what they called old e
nough to go to church they weren't so bothered about us going to the school as long as we went to the church.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you remember any Sunday school outings that you might have gone on?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well nothing, only these walking days that they used to have at
 - like the processions, singing and finishing in the field. Whitsuntide Monday - that was all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You don't remember there being any organized trip out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 No, I don't remember any of those, there didn't used to be }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10574403\charrsid12214547 many}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 . But the ritual that we - when we was getting on towards ten and eleven year old, every }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10574403\charrsid12214547 Easter}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  Monday morning - all the young people of Keighley used to walk to Ilkley. Over the top. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 Across Ilkley Moor, and that was a ritual. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Aye, we used to walk in hundreds over to Ilkley.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Who organized this walk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 But it wasn't really organized, it were just something that happened. That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 It wasn't organized by the Sunday school or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 No. When I got organized with the school it was then during the war like
 when the - the schools used to run football clubs, Ingrow Mission, I played football for Ingrow Mission, me brother played for St John. Somebody played for the - all the schools had football clubs, they used to play one another. But that was when we was 
getting on into the - into the teens really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
What other social activities were organized by the church and which ones did you take part in, you played for a football team for the church, do you remember anything else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 They used to - they used to run - concerts, they used to have concerts but they were quite a few concerts, in the school hall.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Were you ever in them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 I never went in them, but I - no, I - oh no - but me sisters used to do. Norah and Agents they used to take part in them, t
hey used to sing. They used to give plays and musical things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you used to go and watch?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 I've gone and watched 'em, yes, and this were - mind you these were really something outside because there was no other entertainment.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you ever belong to the choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Me? No, they wouldn't have had me in choir if I - but David was, me brother. Oh yes, he was - he was a member of the choir, and me brother that was killed in the first world war, he was a member of the choir.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you belong to any other club organized by the church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you ever join a temperance club run by the church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 No, I don't that I was in anything of that description.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 At home was grace said at meals by your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - at one time I should say yes but this - grew out of the hustle and bustle, it - it faded away.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 As you all got older it stopped?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes. Yes, the - yes, at one time, I've the recollection at one time of this taking place but somehow or other it seemed to -
 to drop out as we got older there was always the hustle and bustle of - well, mealtimes were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 mealtimes}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
, let's get on with the job, you know what it is, we'd to go back to work and it - it - it seemed to drop out. There's nobody - miss it I don't think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Were you taught to say prayers at night before you went to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 We were. When we was children, yes. We was taught, but - this grew - away, we grew away from it. And that were all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you ever have family prayers when you'd all pray together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
No. I wouldn't say that we - I don't recollect such but I do know this, that - when we was taken to bed like - and I'm going back when we were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 really}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  children, that we had to kneel at the side of the bed and say us prayers, we was all brought up to 
do that. But there came a time when of course when you started to take yourself to bed and nobody had time to say that. You just - you just move away from it. We'd been started on this path, that were up to ourselves to - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did your father take an interest in politics, you said he tried to get you interested so he was quite interested himself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well - he was in - he was interested in politics and no doubt - but - but this vague in a lot of things. He was a member of the Railway Servants Associa
tion before it became the Union of Railway - National Union of Railwaymen. And he was also a member of the Labour party when they daren't declare that there was a Labour party. They daren't wear a red rose and when they used to go to meeting they used to 
g
o secretly. I know in - I know that - remember him on one or two more people - going to a political meeting and they had yellow rosettes in. But when they got so far they took these out and went into a place to have the meeting for the Labour party becaus
e - if the police had have got to know they were having they }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 would have}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  raided it. Now I remember that quite plainly. But -

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 That was in Keighley was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 That was in Keighley. And this was before ever I knew what politics was about. It was before the labour party came into -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So your father was a member of the Labour party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Me father - me father would be a member of the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Would it be the I.L.P. then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Probably so. Oh yes, it would be, but it was the Labour movement.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 And he was always a member of the Railways Servants Association?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes, well you see - and - and - these people, they }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 incorporated}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  - they started a lot of this - Independent Labour Party movement. But they used to meet in secret. Oh yes, they had to meet 
in secret. And wherever they had a room to meet they'd always somebody on the door to look out. Now, I don't remember it as a personal thing, I only remember by hearing -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You were a saying your father told you about the Labour party meetings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 O
h yes, I - I can remember him telling about going to - to these meetings, he'd be more or less telling me mother. And of course, being big earned, I - I'd listen and I can remember them wearing - the yellow rosette and then when they got so far they took 
these out and they'd have meetings in various place and - and they had to do it secretly. Otherwise - if the police got to know they would have raided them. But - this is only hearsay, it isn't that I remember it personally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Why do you think he held these views which prompted him to support the I.L.P.?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well - obviously - when - when you've lived in a village - and villages like that me mother and father come from, and you saw the people that had and the people that hadn't, it were bound to have so
me effect on them. Now - a man would work, we'll say, for the Earl of Kirton. He might be a footman he might have been - but his wife also had to work and be a seamstress or do some ironing, washing, and they'd no option. This was all part of it and it wa
s
 just please and thank you father and a lot more of it. And - and I think that a certain amount of resentment grew and grew. 'Til they began to realize that there was one part of the world had it all and the people that created the wealth of the country t
hat enabled them to live as they did got nothing. Now that's - that's my reason for holding those - because I mean I grew up through a period that made me very bitter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You think this is what helped your father to have the views that he had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Because of his earlier years in a sort of feudal sort }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 of affiliation}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
That's right. And then again - lets me fair about this - me dad - he - he married - the - the wages were sixteen shilling a week. Not wit - by that standard it wasn't a lot
, but let's be fair, having a big family kept him poorer. Now there was no help from any welfare state, there was nothing, they had to find - they had to provide for their own flock. It doesn't excuse him from having a big family, being nature being what 
it was, we were there and we were to provide for. And I do believe that having to struggle and struggle and seeing other people - in a different sphere - would make him think. It's bound to do - bound to do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did your mother take an interest in politics at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well - I never heard her declare anything in politics because you must understand that at that time women hadn't a vote. It was only with the - well I do remember hearing a lot about Sylvia Pankhurst and - and the fight for women's rights an
d I can remember when the lady - was killed at the horse racing and - I can remember all this, by hearing them discuss and talk about it. Now, and me mother, when she got the vote, used the vote, I do know this and said that every women ought to.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 They got the vote in 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Yes. And I remember her voting though of course at that time, 1918, we come through a war and you can understand that women that had any sense, they weren't going to vote for anything and any Tom, Dick and Harry were they.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you know what her views were at that time, did she share your father's views?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 
I should imagine so, but I mean - these were very, very - vague, you didn't hear much - discussion about - about this, for the simple reason that when - the woman got 
the vote, I hadn't a vote but I was nearing the point of going - there was young fellows my age already dead in France and - and - and we'd already lost a brother. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Now this - these things made me think for myself. And subsequently after 1918 when the botto
m fell out of the work in Keighley and I was told that I couldn't have any out of work pay, other than what I'd supposedly paid in for, I could have starved, I could have thrown myself in the river, and I was told this by people that lived in Cliffe Castl
e. Now you can understand me and I became very bitter. I was expecting - me father was expected to keep me. And when I went to work on the railway 1922 I left Keighley with a pass provided by the railway. And }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 foupence}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  of me money that me sisters had given me in me pocket and other clothes I stood up in. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 So you can understood what my politics'd be from that point onwards.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You feel that your mother would probably share your father's views?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 I - I - I can't imagine her not doing because - economic circumstances would surely make me mother - feel that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you remember and mother voting in a general election before 1919 and do you know what party they voted for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - I wouldn't know about me mother or ought of that but I certainly know t
hat me dad - who me dad'd vote for, he'd vote for the Labour man. Now I don't know who it would be at that time. But I can remember - Lee Smith and - oh a few more. They're vague in my mind - I - they - I'd have to have 'em brought to me mind to remember.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Was there someone called Baines or Barnes who stood in Keighley?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
There was - Harvey and - I forget really, but - but you can bet your life that when I heard me dad talk about the way they'd gone to those meetings it were obvious the he'd vote for. And he made no bones about it neither.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you remember your mother voting in 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
I remember her saying that she was going to use her vote, and I can only assume that - that the pressures that she'd had on her life up to that time and what 
she'd gone through - would certainly be - for somebody that represented us a little bit more than the other side. To put it -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 In some places at that time men felt they risked losing their job or their house if they voted differently from their employe
rs, do you know if your father felt himself under that kind of pressure, to vote for a particular party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 
Well - I wouldn't really - know that but probably had he have been in a house that, we'll say, belonged to - a - a private firm, yes, it was very, very - rife at that time. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
People in these villages that I do know that - that lived under the farmer or the landowner or the squire - oh they daren't divulge anything other than voting. And they were so frightened that it could be traced that they would 
vote for the people that they represented owing to being in a tied house. Now I do know that, that is a fact. But I wouldn't say that it applied to me dad because we lived in this 'ere little house here and all that that had nothing to do with the railway
. And he was openly a member of the railway servants. Which was recognized by - as far as I'm }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 aware}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  - by the railway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So you don't think the railway would put any pressure on him in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 I wouldn't - I wouldn't really think so, I wouldn't say
. But - at the same time they certainly wouldn't get - a lot of encouragement from the upper strata. What is obvious, but I - I wouldn't know because - he didn't live in a - a railway rented house. Had he have done that I would have probably have heard mo
re, but as I say, I was too young to understand half of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you remember him working for the I.L.P. at an election?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 I can't remember him working - in regard to this - I can - I can remember him talking plenty about it - when the voting is - 
but I wouldn't like to say that I could remember working because, as I say, at that time - any work that were done, God knows when they did it because they were working all hours of the day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did your mother ever join the I.L.P.?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 I shouldn't think so. No, I think me mother's - work were in the home, plenty on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So you don't remember her working for one of the parties?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 No, no, I shouldn't think she would do, no. And - and she didn't enjoy good enough health to be tied to do anything over
 and above 'cos when we all grew up were all prepared to help in our way to ease the burden of -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did your parents take part in any political activities other than at election times?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Not to my knowledge, I wouldn't - I wouldn't like to say -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 But your father used to go to meetings you said?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 Oh me dad'd go to meetings and -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 This was just at election times was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 And - oh and - and he'd go to meetings for the union you know when they held the meetings. But as I say, a lot of th
is was all done - more or less secretly and - and - and of course - there - some of their own members of the fraternity criticized these people for - for taking this militant action, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Their own members?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes, the - the worker has been the biggest enemy to himself of course, and he is still - he still is today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So he would be criticized from within his own union for being politically active?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Let me say - I should imagine he would rather than that I know he was, I should imagin
e, you see, because - I'm having to base some of it on as I grew older. What I learnt by remembering what I'd heard previously. I didn't - the full significance and - at six - seven and eight year old didn't strike me as much as it did when I was eighteen
.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 When your parents were not doing their work how did they spend their time, your father had an allotment didn't he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 That was - that was his main - hobby.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did he ever do anything else other than that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 No, no, no, no. It were his work w
hich as I say - you see - if - the transport - the only transport there was in most of the time was trains. Now in Keighley you know the trams that used to run was horse drawn. I can remember 'em having horses that pulled the trams Long before they had el
ectric trams and - and buses, I can remember the buses were solid }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 tyres}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
 and boneshakers and - and now we've got to the space age, so I've seen the - the - the growth of the transport system. Yes, I can remember that quite well, I - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 in fact}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  I used to go and get hold of the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 horses\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
 heads and bring 'em round the trams at Ingrow.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 And bring them to the other end?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes. Thinking I were doing something. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So your father didn't have much time other than for his allotment and his actual work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 That's right. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did your mother have any interests outside the home, I think you said she was a member of the Churchwomen's Guild or something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - in a - in - as we grew older she - she did that. And I wouldn't like to say that - she wen
t - I think it were more for the - for the company than probably the religious side. And - the - the person at the time when she was ill, Mr Pedley, were very very kind. And so - there was a little mutual respect for the church in that respect. And she di
d go to the church at Sundays, not every Sunday, she' didn't go every Sunday. But latterly she did go to a - I think they called it the Women's Union.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you remember her going out to enjoy herself other than to the Mothers Union?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well not - not 
by herself, but I can remember when she'd - she'd take us to the - to the theatre. The Hippodrome. I've always liked the theatres, I do today, I - I love the live theatre. Sometimes she would - take us to a - the pantomime or a musical show. That - which 
w
as nearly all varieties. If we could afford it she'd take us, now it used to be what - about sixpence up in the gods and we used to go up there. Now I don't say that she took us all but I do remember her taking me a time or two. Probably she took us in us
 turns. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You don't remember her actually going out by herself, without any of you or your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - no, I can't say that - I can't say that I do. I can't - I can't say that I do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 When did your father get home from work in the evenings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well - well he - he - he were very unpredictable owing to the - the place where he worked and - many a time he didn't come home, he would go into lodgings. Into - I think they had a kind of a - what they used to call barracks in those days. And 
- if he was on nights, well I never saw him, if he was on days - if he got home in the evening time well of course, like all fathers he - he'd talk and play but we was - we was out - in our early stages we was out, as we grew older - you know, like same a
s when we got into - started in the mill at twelve and - thirteen then of course - my friends and I we started - what shall we say, like more in the physical culture style. Well we didn't see much of dad, we didn't want to see much of us parents then. No.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 How many evenings a week would he spend at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 me?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
If one week he was working a day shift and he came home at teatime how many nights of that week would he spend at home and how many would he go out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Wel
l I wouldn't - I wouldn't be able to remember that because you see when he had time off really in a - in the - shall we say the summertime - he'd be in the garden. Mostly he would either be coming or going, he'd - he'd got to get his rest to be off again 
the next day - to go to his work you see. They couldn't afford to go - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 Idling}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
 as they could today. They'd come home for their food and - and to be at home mostly. I do recollect him - if he got a weekend - off, which he would be entitled to I suppose at som
e time, going and playing cricket for the railway team. I can remember - him doing that but I wasn't all that interested in going - he didn't want us with us, I mean, we'd have been a nuisance wouldn't we at that time. And - of course as I got }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 old enough}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  to play myself well I wanted to be playing myself, not -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did your father attend any clubs or pubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well I wouldn't - I wouldn't say he was what you would call an attender but without a doubt he'd - he'd - he'd be - what shall I say - pop in - to 
- I don't suppose he'd any really set place. I think he used to go to one of the - a club - and have a game of billiards with - some of his colleagues. But this were few and far between. He hadn't the time and I don't suppose they had the money to spend o
n such things really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So he didn't go very regularly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well I wouldn't like to say that he went regularly because - I don't recollect - him doing that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did your mother ever go with him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh no, no, that - not - not an any - not an any jaunts of that kind.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you remember any other sport he did other than cricket?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well - no, I don't recollect him taking part in any sport apart from him playing the occasional cricket. Because he was getting on then. But as a boy - and of course 
this were before ever he met me mother, he used to be a runner, on a - you know, run races and that was a - a good runner. And I suppose I - follow in his footsteps in that respect 'cos I'm quite a speed merchant myself like. As a boy. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 But that was long, long way back.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did your father ever attend horse races?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well - I have a recollection of him going to see his sister that lived at - they moved from Brinklow where they was born, to Chester. In other words they went to a place called Kirkness whic
h is now an atomic centre. Capenhurst in Chester. Capenhurst, yes. And it's in - today it's a - atomic centre, but at that time a nice lovely little village, and he used to go to Chester races. But not much. High day come holiday, you know. And he went to
 see his own sister then. But of course - I was - it was only something that I heard him talk about, I don't -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you ever hear him mention that he had a bet when he went to the races?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - I don't - I wouldn't say that I'd heard him bet - I heard him talk about - such things like as all men talk about. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 Sport, horse racing, even I talk about it but I wouldn't risk a penny on a horse, I'd be frightened to death of losing it, but - he could - he could have had a bet but if he did I don't know whe
re he got his money to - to take the bet with because I mean money were in very, very short supply in those days.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did your father or mother belong to any savings clubs, such as a boot club, a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 sick}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  club or a funeral club in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - not
 to my knowledge, I think - if they did have anything it might have been a kind of insurance in case of - of death, you know, at one time. They did. This had to be a must, I do recollect something to do with insurance but I think it were that if ought hap
pened to us we - some - something to put - put us away with and that was - that's about all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Was this a funeral club sort of?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well it - it was like an insurance effort but whether it was for any other purpose I don't recollect, I - I rather doubt it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 How did you get on with your brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Oh - I got - reason - reasonably well, like all brothers and sisters, we - got on well together, we - we fought and fell out and fell in and - helped one another and did for one another an
d - it were like ought else, if we fought among ourself we took good care that nobody else fought - that was when we were all - we were a family and very close together and have remained so the whole of us life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Was there one sister or brother that you felt particularly close to at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well - no, I wouldn't say - that we was any closer but sister Norah that is now seventy-three year old - was more or less - my age and - she used to - go to the pictures, we used to go to the pictures togeth
er. And - and as she grew older and they - they tried to learn me to dance but I weren't having any of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So your sister Norah, who was the one just a little bit older than you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes, she's three years older than me, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 As a child do you remember who you played with chiefly, was it your brothers and sisters or neighbours children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Oh no. There were - I had - what we referred to in Yorkshire as mates. Oh yes, there was what - two, three, four or five. And of course my brothers. I sh
ould imagine mostly - there was seven - seven of us involved together. And as we grew older - we had a - in - and went into Brier Street, it had a big attic. Now we turned that into a gymnasium. And we used to meet there - most nights, especially in the w
inter. And we had - the usual things, and parents clubbed up to help buy 'em and we had to save us bit of spending money, to get punch balls and boxing gloves and - and - wrestling. Now we used to do all this, we - even made us own parallel bars to do }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 gymnastics}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
. Now this were our pastime. But this is when we were getting into twelve year old, thirteen year old. And this carried on 'til - we started courting and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 When you were playing away from your own home did you play in the yard or in the garden or
 in the street or at other homes of children or elsewhere?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well it - it was mostly - in the recreation - we were fortunate enough to be in a place where there's a big recreation field that was given by Sir John Clough to the people of Springbank to p
lay in, and that's where we spend ninety percent of our time and if we did play near home and we played on the roads you must understand that time that the traffic that was likely into interfere with us was horses and carts. And there weren't many of thos
e.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you have a yard with your house?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
There was a yard in Brier Street but there was no yard - no garden or anything else in Hazel Street. There was a yard at the back in Rawlings Street, a yard in Brier Street and - and a little garden that you could probably - the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 size}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  of a postage stamp. And - no, we didn't play much in the yards, we wanted to be far enough away from home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 When you did play out with the other children what games did you play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well the usual - the usual games were 
cricket, football - running, wrestling, we used to think nothing of running what we used to call - chasing each other. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 
One had to be - the - the hare, the hound or this sort of thing, and we thought nought of running - miles. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Miles. I've run round from Hazel - here to Cullingworth. In evening time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 That's about six or seven miles isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes, and we thought nought about it. Today they won't walk as many yards as we run miles.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 No other games that you can think of that you played?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 W
ell the games you know was - the girls used to play - checks, you know, the - they used to bounce a - a ball and pick the checks up, have you ever seen them play? Checkers they used to call them and they used to have several square pieces of - I don't kno
w
 what they were made of - like pot or - they used to bounce a ball and pick so many up and catch them. Now these - this was a proper girl's - and then there was shuttlecock, they used to play shuttlecock, which is - badminton if you wish, in its own game.
 
And the boys, we used to play tennis. But we'd no racquets, it used to be boards - anything you could make yourself. And - we had no real football to play football, we used to get a - an old bag and fill it with paper and stuff it out. We couldn't afford 
a ball.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Were you allowed to get dirty when you played out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well I - I don't know whether we were really allowed to get dirty but we did. You - you see you couldn't avoid it because - the thing was this, that if we got dirty we certainly had to get washed, and that were a big thing like.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Were you free to play with anyone you pleased?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Oh - yes, yes, there was no - there was no really no embargo on anyone to play with, mind you there were - there was certain - children at that time that we
re verminous and - there were many a time I know if we'd been playing around with a lot that many a time when we used to be thoroughly combed over. Oh yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Your mother was making sure you hadn't caught anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes, oh yes, and this used to be a ritual. But we was not -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did they everyday that you hadn't to play with these children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 No, no. We }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 was not}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  - we wasn't stopped from playing anywhere. And I can't ever remember - anything to lead us to be discriminating - by anything. I think 
we was more or less made - or allowed to make up us own mind because - everybody has their likes and dislikes. And I suppose as children we had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You were never actually discouraged from playing with certain children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 No, we - I don't recollect ever - being barred.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you belong to any youth organizations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
No, not - not really. As I say, as we grew older and we - we played football - for the - the school and all that. No, not - not to - my time when I left school in 1912 - I then went 
four nights a week to the night school for four and a half years, so I hadn't - much time for anything. In that respect.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you have any hobbies when you were still at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well, me hobbies was really - drawing. I used to love to draw. And -
 and write Now - like all other boys, if it came to playing - I had the - the toy soldiers and - and that type of thing but I mean this was a - a recognized toy for all boys.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you keep any pets at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 I remember - I remember having a couple of rabbits - at one time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you look after them, were they yours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
We looked after them for a certain period of time and then of course it were left to the parents to look after them. And one day they disappeared and - and when I wanted t
o know where they were me mother had said, well you didn't look after them so that's it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you remember collecting things such as postage stamps or anything else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 No, the only thing that - the cheapest thing that we could collect at that time -
 there used to be cigarette cards in cigarette packets and anyone that smoked well of course - every child was after the cigarette cards. And - and sometime now they'd fetch rather a fabulous amount of money if you'd a good set. We - and we used to exchan
g
e them one with another. Now also there used to be football cards - what they called football cards, you can see 'em in the museum today. And these were - a penny a packet to buy. Now - or a ha'penny a packet. Now - a lot of money out of your spending mon
e
y, 'cos your spending money were about, what - threeha'pence a week or - tuppence. And we used to play a game in throwing them on the pavement and when they overlapped you see, the one that overlapped the other took - took the - the cards, and we used to 
play hours at this game.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you ever go fishing while you were still at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Fishing? Well if did it were only - it were only to get so as that I could play about in the water in the river, it weren't that I were fishing, I - I weren't particularly keen on fishing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you go for walks at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Yes, we used to go - walking quite a lot, all the seven of us. And we spent hours up on Harding Moor and round - where the guide is today. What they call Harden - Hardens Moor and - and the f
arm. There was plenty of walks. Hainworth, a lovely little village even today. Yes, we used to walk, but, mind you, we was - at the same time we was more or less - playing a game if you like that - we could have either been }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 centurions}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  or gladiators or - yes, or - we - we fancied ourself as mountaineering, climbing up the old quarries.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you ever go with friends or was it nearly always with brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 No, no. The - we - me - sisters didn't go. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 
You - you didn't - you didn't take girls with you, you know in those days, oh no. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 It was mostly the boys and - there - there used to be about seven }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 of}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So there'd be your brothers and some friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes, and - and boyfriends and all this - all - about the same age.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you have a bicycle at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 A bicycle? Good heavens, there nobody could afford a bicycle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you take part in any sports yourself at that time before leaving school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - well - well only sport as we made it ourselves you see, we used to fa
ncy ourselves as being gymnastic. This was - when we were getting up towards teenagers and thinking -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Just before you left school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Before you left school. At school - no, it - it was a case of running in the school sports, you know, they used t
o have these 'ere school sports. To us it was just a - an afternoon out away from schooling and - we used to run and jump like all the schoolchildren. But - nothing really particularly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you go to the theatre, concerts, music halls, cinemas while were still at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well - if we went to concerts, it - it was these that was given - by the - the church or the Sunday school and of course - they used to ask if we'd take part. But this chicken never play - I - I never fancied myself -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You used to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 go}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  and watch them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Oh I'd go for watch - anywhere to go - I love music and listen to singing. Even as a child, but I could never afford to go to - to pay to - hear - I never thought of it in that light of course I mean - you don't think of thes
e 'til you start to mix up with people at work, then you be more - you become something different.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 How about theatres and concerts, I think you said your mother occasionally took you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes, and they were few and far between, very few and far between.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What sort of a theatre was it that she took you to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh it was mostly Keighley Hippodrome. Of course it's since been pulled down now and incorporated -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Was it music hall they had there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 It was called - the - Keighley Hippodrome - 
Queens Theatre and Hippodrome. Usually there was varieties - and there was such as Marie Lloyd - oh - I forget the names. George }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 Formby}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  - Florrie Ford and all that crowd they used to come. Quite some well known people. And I remember - as I was getting on 
at - getting older at this time when Gracie Fields and Archie Pitt came up to Keighley and missed the Tower of London. Now that's going back a bit. I remember them playing, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you go to the cinema?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 That was going up towards - what - 1912, 1913 - oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you go to the cinema before you left school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh - we went to the - we went to the - the cinema before we left school. What was it, Saturday afternoon sometimes, I think it was a - a }
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 penny}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 . And - and this was of course it beca
me a treat, it was in the silent days you know of - you - you get a glaring example of - mad movies, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 Monkhouse's}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
 mad movies or the Golden Showere. All those sort of films, yes, and believe it - they was good in that day and yes, and you got quite a laugh out of them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did your parents give you any pocket money at all at that time before you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - if we was given - what - I should say a copper or two, I - I really don't know the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 exact}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  amount but it weren't much because - if we used to go and get a few sweets that was it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 And that was what you spent it on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you get it fairly regularly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 We were supposed to get these - what they call Saturday pennies at - weekend. And it - and it - and it was pence. There 
was no doubt about that. We - we never had money to - to spend.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did anyone outside the home help your mother look after her house or family, other than the lady that she paid to help her do the washing?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did relations or friends or neighbours come in and help her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Oh no, no, it was all - it was all done on - on our own. The point as far as I can remember is that - we all had little jobs to do like and that was it. And the girls, as they grew older, well of course they - used 
to do quite a lot, I can remember them - you know, when they took over and started to do a lot of the washing. And believe me there was some washing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 If your mother was ill or confined to bed how did she manage then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - there was many a time
 when me mother - was ill but I don't recollect her being confined to bed until - yes, she used to have some tremendous headaches. Well we used to all have to do the best we could, she used to lay down and - and then of course the - the two girls and - an
d
 - maybe there might have been a neighbour come in to help as far as I that but I don't recollect anything like that, we used to have to make the best out we could. But it were like ought else in those days mothers used to have to work if it killed them. 
There's no doubt about that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you remember fairly clearly what happened when your brother David was born? You won't remember anyone else being born will you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 I can remember - I can remember him - as a baby but I can't remember - that he - that
 it was of any importance except that it was another baby. No, I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So you don't remember of the younger ones actually being born, you don't remember what happened?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh no, no. There were - they was there. Me mother was at home, there's no doubt a
bout that, all this happened at home. And - and how we didn't know or how it was kept from us I wouldn't know, it - it's a case of this, probably we weren't over interested. But when they came we were there, of course he'd been either found in a cabbage p
a
tch or - or he'd just come, somebody had picked him up and that were it. We weren't even bothered, he were there and - he was a brother and - the youngest sister and she was a sister and - and of course we grew up together, they was just part of a family,
 just another to - another - another mouth of feed that was all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did your parents have any relatives living nearby at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - not really what you could call relatives you see, she'd relatives that was direct relatives they were - more or less
 all away. Except - as I say me mother had a brother that lived - in Keighley, in Pickles Street, as far as I knew. Very likeable chap, very nice jolly fellow used to come and visit us. In Pickles Street. That's in - as far as I remember, he might have li
ved somewhere else previous to it but I couldn't tell you about that but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Pickles Street was quite near to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 How much did you see of him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh about - about once a year he used to come and - once a - once a week he'd probably
 pop in. Sundays, he used to call in at Sunday. I think it were a - a ritual more or less.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you ever go to his house to see him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes, but - I went more after - I'd started work. I went more to see - to - to see him in 1918, you see, they were
 getting older and he was a - a joiner carpenter and that time their job covered interior decorating and that's how I come to be involved with this. And I used to - he - he was doing his own house one day and I went and started to help him and - and from 
that time on I - I did, took interest in it, loved it and - that became my hobby from 1918.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did your parents have any friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well no more than shall I say the ordinary - relatives and probably neighbours as they are. You know. I don't recollec
t anything more or less - to say that they was going out to friends or meeting friends to go anywhere, I don't recollect any of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did they share the same friends more or less?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well, if there were they would do because I mean - it was all - p
art of the same area, everybody - there's - there's nobody at that time - had any money to go anywhere.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So they didn't go out visiting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 No, no. Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Or had visiting them at their house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 There was nobody came to have a - to really stay, that I can - and anyway there weren't room. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Did your mother or father have friends of their own, did your mother have friends and your father have friends that weren't friends of the other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well, if me dad had friends to - to be friends,
 it would be - the colleagues that he worked with, as my colleagues became mine in the passage of years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Were friends ever invited into the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well, we was this type of a family and we've remained that way that we was an ever open door for an
yone that cared to come and if there was anything that was eatable and they wanted it they could have it, they could share, they could join and probably I should imagine many a time the parents would probably go short to let someone else have it. This was
 a -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you remember anyone actually being invited into the house for a meal or for an evening or something like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 No, I can't - I can't say that I - I would say that there was any really what you could call invitations, it - if - if there wa
s anyone came - to me they came.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 It was just a question of just }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 casually}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 coming}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 More or less, I should imagine so. And we've all - and we are even like that today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 They were mainly neighbours were they, the people who did this popping in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
I should imagine - well I should imagine so really. I - I mean to - before I left school people didn't really interest me up to a point. I - my - my life were - were mine, I - I - as long as there was something on the table that I could eat and -
 and when it were bedtime I resented being called in to go to bed. Like all the rest of the children. But I wasn't particularly interested in - the activities of me parents, except that they were - me mother was always there. And me dad was either coming 
or going. And - he was supposed to be the bread winner but God }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 knows}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  how they - how they won anything in these days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 People often tell us that in those days they made their own amusements, what do you think your parents did when they were together with
 their friends and neighbours and the people who used to sort of casually come in in an evening, would they have music or games?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 There were no music, we - we'd no - no - no, if they - if they played anything - it might have been a game of cards, domi
noes, draughts - or that type of game. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 
And this is the type of thing that we - used to play, ludo, parchesi and - snakes and ladders, all these things, and there was other games that they used to play and - I nearly forget what they were - in - in - making
 - making games of your own by - drawing and making certain things from one line into another to see what you could turn it into. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 This was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 home life}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  like, you used to make your amusements, yes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 
There was games - that if we were lucky - I think they call it the same - Monopoly and - that type of thing, patience. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Otherwise there was no - there were no such thing as a piano, music, }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 gramophone}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
 or ought of that and if there was any singing - then it was only the singing that you would automatically burst out into in an ordinary way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You wouldn't all sing together, the people who came in to visit you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh if anyone come in to visit us there'd be no singing and that. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 But you played games in your house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes, yes, the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you remember your mother and father calling into other peoples' houses and doing the same, playing games?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
I don't recollect them. If they did then - this could have been well after I - we'd gone to bed. I doubt it, I don't think - I - I never recollect us being }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 left}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  in the house on us own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Many people divide society into different social classes or groups, in that time before 1918 did you think of some people belonging to one and some to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 There was only two classes. In my - way of thinking.
 And that was that we had nothing. And others had something. And it boiled down to the difference in work. I changed me mind a lot as I grew older. But at that time - at that time, we - were like most people that lived in that community.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 So you more or less divided them into the haves and the have- nots?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 It's what it boiled down to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Which class or group would you say you belonged to yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - at that time I should that we belonged to what would be termed poor. And - hard working
 people, but there's no doubt that we're poor because - we had to make do and mend with anything that was going. And money was in short supply so we couldn't be anything else but poor. And we was taught to be very careful.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What sort of people belonged to the same class or group as yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well - it was a - a question of this, that - that the people in our sphere worked in the mill. Long hours, low pay. There was the - the occasional }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 overlooker}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 , well of course - a man that was an overlooker he was rather looked upon as being affluent, he was. The station m}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10574403\charrsid12214547 aster}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  at Ingrow station, he was as big as the Lord Mayor of London, you know. Apart from that the others were engineers and - at that time I suppose when they was working like that - if they had
 a big family then they were in the same category as us. If they had only one maybe two, then they were better off. It boiled down to - practically the same crowd.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What would you say were the sort of people who belonged to the other classes? What about the people who had more than you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well - they - every - they were all - all right, I mean, the people immediately in what we term the working class movement, were just - they were workers, I mean, the - there was no difference in the - in - what sh
all we day - a dividing line, there was no dividing line, it was just that if they were working and - and a little better wage and less to pay out to feed a flock then they had more to do on. It was as simple as that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 They were the people who were slightly better off?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes. But - we had - people that Sir John Clough - the owner of the mill as lived up on the - Spring }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10574403\charrsid12214547 B}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 ank estate. Woodhouse Estate had a - a big house that overlooked the whole of the town. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 
Now - he - used to come up in horse and cart and of course - he - he'd be one that had the first motor car that came in. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
And the people that lived up Woodhouse Road were not allowed to hang their washing out - owing to the fact that he didn't wish to see any body's washing hung out as he went by a
nd it were as simple as that. And these people thought that you had - to bow and scrape to them. And it was Sir John Clough or it was Lady Clough or it was - the daughters whose names I've forgotten. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did they own the houses on Woodhouse Road?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well I - probably at one time they might have done but I wouldn't know. I - I don't know if they owned - we paid rent as I say at that time, I wasn't interested in it. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 
But - I do know that if these people were about you were expected to stop breathing while they passed you, you see.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What sort of people would you say they were, what sort of class would you put them into?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well these - these were the - the people that held the power of the mills had the power to - employ you, the power to sack y
ou, the power to - to deal with you. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So it was the employer sort of class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes, they - they - they owned the mills, Clough}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10574403\charrsid12214547 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 s mill, Haggas's mill and - there was - all where the houses, Bratton Bank and all these places are built now the
y were all fields that belonged to them. But their built on now, but they sold them - they sold it out to make money no doubt. But these were the - what we referred to as the upper strata. And - I aren't going to say that they were - that they were bad pe
o
ple, they were born into this - life, and lived accordingly. But - when you grow older and realize the - the difference - in - the people that create the wealth for those that are getting the best of it and then you change your mind. But this of course de
veloped during the war. And mostly after the war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Can you remember being brought up by your parents to treat people on one sort differently from people of another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Not exactly - not exactly to be different except that we was - taught this way, that these people had this power - of - some control }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 over}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
 them, would - really didn't sink in as to what they really meant. I mean - Cloughs, Haggas's and - all these people - they were somebody that we were supposed to - give a kind of a reverence to. But a
t the same time - we wasn't - we wasn't encouraged to do any bowing or scraping. But we was - we was told that these people were who they were. It's only when you grew older that you began to realize the difference.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Were you ever told to touch your cap or show respect in some way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Would it be to these people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
No, not just to these people. You see - it didn't matter whether - shall we say, a - a woman or a girl, didn't mater what sphere she was - but she was a - a lady to 
us and - and it was a man's duty to show a respect to a woman. And even to that day, that goes for me too - I have no - I have no sirs in my life that means sir because of his social standing and all that. A sir to me would be a man that had shown me the 
s
ame respect as I expect from everybody. And I often refer it if I meet somebody and - a lorry driver might stop his lorry and say, now then, can you tell me I can - yes, sir, I can tell you or I can't tell you. No more than that. It's a - a figure of spee
ch to me to give respect to other folk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 When you were younger were you ever taught to call anyone sir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
No, I - I can't say that I was really taught to that but we did - we did hear these - people referred to as that but I wouldn't say that I was - really - taught to call anyone that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 In the district, you called it the Woodhouse Estate district did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well, yes, the Springbank }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 Ingrow}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 . Ingrow. Where we spent most of us childhood.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 In this district who would you say was considered the most important people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh the most important people were actually - were - was - old Doctor Crawford that lived in lodgings at the bottom of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 Brier}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  Street. He was one. Then of course there was Sir John Clough - and - his daughters and - and they liv
ed all over. Then of course there was Haggas that lived at the other side - that owned }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 Haggas's}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
 mill. These of course were eminent people as far as that time was concerned. But in regard to anyone immediately around about well - no, I can't say that - ther
e was one gentleman - a very nice fellow and they called him - Smith. And he had a greenhouse. And when we used to play cricket - we used to - break an occasionally window and it used to cost us a penny to have these windows put in. And the - son used to 
play with us and he became the Lord Mayor of London, Sir Bracewell Smith. But he was a boy playing in the cricket field with us at cricket, football and - circumstances, he turned out to be - bought }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 Cliff}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  Castle, that's in Keighley, and presented it to the town. But -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Were that family of Smith's important at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well - do more important than that - that he had a decent job he might - he - his father. Oh yes, had a good job, not like people that were schoolteachers. Obviously they had a nice going on, the station }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10574403\charrsid12214547 master}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  at Ingrow station - Oakworth and all - these were - big fellows. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 
They was - certain men in the mills that had - what we used to call walking bosses, they used to go down to make sure that everybody were working. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 I - when I wo
rked in the mill I've seen girls cry because these people have come round and - and told them to get on with their work, their - heads down and all that. And it was at that time when I used to start to resent - this treatment. But this is going outside - 
the 1918 period, I mean, I'd left - when I started to resent this. The
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 These people in the district who were considered important, did you come into contact with them at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 eeh}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  - one - one man that was an overlooker at Cloughs mill, I - mates and - his son, his two sons, we went about together and played together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you ever come into contact with Sir John Clough or Haggas's?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 I've come in contact with Haggas's - they were quite nice peoples. Sir John Clough we didn't meet up
 - much and we took good care that his gamekeeper didn't catch us when we were after his apples. You see, we were lads when all was said and done.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Why would you say that these people were considered important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - they were - there wasn't - t
hey were in - the people that were important were of course the people that owned the mills and the factories. And they were the only ones that - that we considered. The other people - overlookers, they - they had good jobs and that but there was no discr
i
mination, the boys and the girls and - and that, they mixed up with us. There was no reason why they shouldn't because - even then - although they had the good jobs they were just as likely to come under the hammer of the powers that be, if they over step
ped the mark. In other words they had to be slave drivers to keep people slaves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What about the shopkeepers in the district, who did they associate with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - the shopkeepers in that - in my opinion - locally - they're still there anyway, they 
were all friendly people for the simple reason that they wanted what bit of money you had, they wanted it to make a living out of. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So they were friends with the local people?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 And - they - the one that today has done very, very wel
l, they'd sell anything and - but - and - I should imagine they'd make more money by selling ha'porths of things than they would by selling penn'orths and shillings. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Who would you say the clergy associated with, the vicar of various churches?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
What the - the clergy? Well to my way of thinking the only people that they had room for - mind you, I might be a little bit biased now, I - I wouldn't give it so much thought as a child as I've given it since and probably - my mind's going back
 now from today, instead of yesterday. But they always seemed to have room for the people that could put the money in the collection box. And - and I still believe it's the same today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 How about the teachers, who did they associate with mainly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well I wouldn't know who they associated with but I got on very well with the schoolteachers at school. I don't say that I - I was a - a good scholar and I don't say that I was any better behaved than any other child, but - discipline was so good and so s
trong that we did behave ourselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 But you don't know what the teachers did outside of school hours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
No, no. No, these people were of course more or less a class of their own - they always were under the impression that when they left school the
y was cluttered up with work to get ready for the next day. Which to me was - become a fallacy like. Since that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you know any farmers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Farmers? Yes, I - I knew a - I knew a farmer and the - they called him Feather.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Who would you say his friends were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well I wouldn't now who his friends were but his two sons were - rather friendly with the boys of Springbank. And they - had a farm up towards Hainworth and - we used to go up to help them like, put the cows in, it was only a matt
er of going up to - to pass time on and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So their sons were friendly with the working class boys of the area?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes, and - one - one became a - I believe he became an auctioneer, an auctioneer or valuer, something of that. And the second son i
s living today, they call him Ivor Feather, he's a - an auctioneer - in Keighley. They was grand people. There was nothing about them - and he was - smashed up by a bomb - during the war he was a big smart fellow and now he's a little old man, he isn't as
 old as me. But - they were farmers.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 And they associated with people in the district?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Of course - yes, the boys you see, the - the boys used to play with us and of course being on a farm they had chores to do. And of course every so often we use
d to go up - pretending to help, if we put the cows in the stall or fetched them in or ought of that. This was a big job that we'd done, but it - it were really nothing when you come - when you come to think about it later.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What about the employers, Sir John Clough and Haggas's, who were their friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well - you wouldn't know them, the only friends that they would have would be in the same category as them selves. They were - what would be at that time, society, and I mean - they were - really -
 somebody - that had no time for no one else only those people in their own sphere. Which was of course the mill owners, the mine owners of different places, I mean you didn't see these people, they lived at - they lived on - on their own and lived their 
own lives.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So the people that visited them would be from other areas, people of a similar sort of income?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Oh - they - oh they - they - they were - they had their own social life as much as it is today. I mean, I could win the pools of about what 
- five or six hundred thousand pound tomorrow but I would never be accepted in their society would I. No, we wouldn't, you couldn't get in. You couldn't get in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you think you could draw a distinction between the people who went to the church and th
e people who went to the chapel, or would you say they were similar?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well - well to me they were - they were all - much the same, because me brother Frank that was killed - in the first world war - he was brought up Church of England. And then he wan
ted to play football with some of his mates that were Wesleyans, so he went to the Wesleyans. And - when he joined up in 1916 to avoid some of these Church parades, he became a Roman Catholic. So, on paper - he - he was anything that would suit him. Yes. 
A
nd - there was some very nice people that went to the Wesley Place chapel, there were some nice people went to the church and even today I have not a clue what the difference is between Roman Catholicism, Church of England, Wesley Place Baptist - or the Q
uakers, it - to me it's something that - I'm afraid I haven't really a lot of - thought. I've been in the Vatican city at - in Rome and seen all the pomp and pageantry and - and - the silliness of it. Let me - and I'm quite }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 candid}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 , but that's today, not when I was a child.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
So you couldn't tell me what sort of people they were particularly who went to the church and to the chapel at that time, whether there was any difference?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 No, no. No. I - I wouldn't - I wouldn't be able to - to tell the differ
ence, I wouldn't really know. And I don't know why the difference in the places.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Would you say the wealthier elements went to the church or would you say it was evenly divided?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 The only difference that I can say is this, that the people that wen
t to the church were - were patronized by the - the people that was in this society of mill owners and - and the wealthy people. But the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you not get this as much going to the chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 But there didn't seem to be the same people go to the ch
apel. And where - you got people in the role of shall we say - vicars, parsons, whatever you lie, they call them speaking in the church you got the ordinary layman speaking in the chapel. But apart from that it wouldn't - it didn't convey ought to me at t
hat time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Where you lived did all the people in the working class have the same standard of living or would you say there were different groups? You told me that there were overlookers and that there were people who only had one or two children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes. Yes. But even so -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Could you describe to me a family in each group, or if you could just label the different groups within the working class, you felt that you were quite poor, would you say that there was an even poorer group than your family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
I wouldn't - yes, I daresay there were because - like my dad - by being on the railway was regularly employed. He - he had what they call a full time job and if it hadn't have been for having seven mouths to feed, which was entirely his own fault, he 
would probably have been much better off. Now there was some that were labourers that had probably as big a family and they was laid off in bad weather. Now - how they did I do not know, so there could be some slightly poorer, there was some slightly bett
er and - but I think that it was mostly a question of - the number of the family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Do you think you could describe a certain family in each group, in the labourers group, the people who were sometimes out of work, can you remember a family at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
I can - I can remember - I can remember families - in - living but I couldn't say that their circumstances seemed any different to my own, because, you see - when we went and mixed up with them there was no difference carry on in their homes than th
ere was in me own. I wouldn't like to say that although a - a man was working we'll say. employed in a mill as an overlooker which would be quite a nice wage - I don't say that he had anything more to throw away, probably be able to get things better and 
more quickly. But - no - it wouldn't be 'til years after when things became - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 stabilised}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
, you see, that I mean - there was a lot of difference when the war broke out in the way things - changed and altered. A difference in - in the money and circumstances a
nd as you know there came then after the war in 1918 - the greatest depression of all time struck the country. And that made it worse still. But that's going into 1918, 1919.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So you can't particularly describe a group and how it differed from the way
 you lived, you couldn't say that they had a better house or better food or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh - well - well - oh yes - there's some - one or - one or two had - larger houses.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 The overlookers could afford a better house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well it - it -
 I don't suppose we - really it was much affording as being able to have one. You see, at that time, houses were many a time - it was nothing to see a notice in - this house to let. Now if you could get one - of course, the bigger the house of course the 
d
earer the rent and of course - now - I know an overlooker that - he just had the two boys - three boys, and they lived in a similar house to me - to what we lived in. Their circumstances would be better that - probably have a little more money coming in a
n
d consequently they could buy - probably better food - few better clothes. But apart from that it didn't strike any difference. Now I had another friend, he had two daughters - three daughters and a boy. Now they lived in a house that was a through house,
 
they had a yard. Now this was quite something. They had like a - a living room - a sitting room or whatever you like to call it, a kitchen, that you could move about in. This was quite a big house. And if we did play out and played in the yard this was so
mething. - but - at that time you could play in the street, you could play in the road, there weren't so many children, there weren't so many - there were no traffic.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you think that one group felt itself superior to the rest, within the working class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 It is quite possible that they might have done. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 
But I - I wouldn't say that I took any notice of it at that time. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
It was only - after the 1918 war that when you realized - that the people that sat in judgement on the working man himself was the wo
rking man himself. Because I was accused of being out of work and not wanting any. And this came from people that were fortunate enough to be working. But to say that I realized it when I was a child at school I would be lying, because I didn't.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do y
ou think that - do you remember any families that were thought of as being rough and other families as were thought of as being particularly respectable?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 Oh - you - you don't - you got the families that - might have been classed as being rough - for 
the simple reason that - I - I don't really know how to explain myself - the - rougher in their ways, rougher in their speech - but not necessarily any worse for being that. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
You - you get - boys that's always }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 seem}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  to be in trouble, of course they were clas
sed as rough. But there was no reason to say that because they were caught being rough that we weren't. No, there - there was - a person were considered rough if he were - if he was - a bit ragged and all that sort of thing. But probably mother could mend
 his pants and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 tonight}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 , next day }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 he\rquote d}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  come home with them torn again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you remember any families in the working class being thought of as particularly respectable?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh - I remember - I remember one or two - of where they - did keep themselves mo
re or less to themselves with a view to - shall we say - hoping to bring probably the child or the children up, into a good education. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 
Which meant that these - people more or less isolated theirself and spent part time in trying to teach - the children, and probably themselves. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
There was that but to me it wasn't so manifest, I didn't realize this 'til years later.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you remember there being a distinction of this kind between craftsmen and labourers at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well, a craftsman, you see, every
one who could had to learn a trade, this was a ritual in those days where if you could you'd to learn - I was put to learning - engineering. I didn't know - I knew nothing about engineering. I could have gone to have been a joiner. I would have loved to h
a
ve gone out and been a - an interior decorator. But it needed money to go into it. No one had any money to pay for these things to be done so that was taboo. And of course I got a two foot rule and a pair of overalls and I was a big man. And I'd never hav
e been an engineer from that day to this.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did your mother and father have the same attitude to people in difference classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes, I think - mind you, the point is this, that if they - they met up with these people that we classed as somebody, I s
uppose there was that bit of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 deference}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
 you know - that they were - someone belonging to these people. I wouldn't say that - I remember much about it, but I have that feeling that that would happen because - this was a thing that these people looked upon as a right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you think your mother saw herself as belonging to a particular class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
No. I think me - me mother - had she have not had so much work and probably enjoyed better health would have liked to have all done shall we say - better for ours
elves. Mother - had that idea, she would have liked to be - her own ambition was for me to have been a guard on a railway. Now I don't know why. I suppose in the old days when she met me dad, a guard was considered to be - quite a - a big noise, he'd a lo
vely uniform, he had quite a decent wage. I went through all those stages and me mother never realized that I had been and passed all this sort of business that she was quite for in the old days.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Was it possible at that time to move from one class to another do you think, can you remember any-one who did this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well, the only way that you could move from - from one sphere to another was by - getting shall we say a better job and - and commanding a bigger rate of pay, going into a better house and 
when the time come that you wanted to buy your own house then of course you'd moved then - oh yes, then you began to think that you were somebody and were -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you remember a family who did this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Not - not really particularly you see, because wh
en it came to - the come - to buying a house it was a case of this, that people began to say, well I'm paying so much in rent, I may just as well try and get a mortgage, pay it on and the house is mine. And - eventually it became that - they're still doin
g it - today. Except that the prices and income and interest has different. It was still just as bad to pay. But his was something that - the - started to learn to do. People wanted to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 sell}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  the houses. And so therefore - they rented - it got less, less, less and less.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you remember seeing a policeman around where you lived as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes. Yes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 
the policeman used to come walking round, and one in particular, Bobby Yeller, he were a big strong chap and if he caught thee they used to give us a - a
 - a clout with his cape, whether we'd done ought or not, that were just to remind us that he was about and he was the boss and he - we could do with more of that today. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
He were - he were a well respected fellow. He - he was good, he'd talk to us but if we
 - did ought wrong I mean - we got into mischief, then we made sure that he didn't - catch us if - if he was coming round we disappeared. For no reason at all, we weren't - we weren't exactly frightened of him but we knew that if we got into trouble we co
u
ld be taken and summonsed and probably - chastised or something of that or - and we - many a time if we was getting a bit obstreperous me mother or me dad might have said, all right, when Bobby comes on we'll have him - we'll have him to you. Well - that 
were the time for us top disappear to make sure he didn't - oh yes, it were grand to have the policeman walking round. And I wish there was more or it today. I do.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 The houses that you lived in were all rented, did you see anything of your landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
I have a recollection of him coming to collect but I - I wouldn't like to say that I remember him, it - you see, by moving from Hazel Street to Rawlings Street back to Brier Street, I do know that the man that - we rented it off in Brier Street - he bo
ught his house through a - bank while we was in it and then - after he'd bought it - he claimed - he claimed the house for his daughter, and of course - my people had to get out of it. And that forced their hand then to go in to purchase a house. In Pickl
es Street. But this of course happened - oh yes, after - after the - after the world war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you remember having and feelings about him as a landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - no, I remember him - agreeing to having the - the fire - the fireplace painted and all t
his kind of thing. So I assume by that he - he wasn't a bad chap really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you remember feeling that your parents had to struggle at that time to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes, I think it were one continual.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 But did you realize this at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Not to the extent that the struggle - was as intense as it might have been. I mean, you don't think about this as a child. These things come and you realize it later but I do know this, that there was never any money floating around for anything. An
d they made no bones about it, if - if we wanted out they used to just say, well - you can't get it without money, I've no money. I shan't have any 'til your dad comes home with his wage on - I think they used to get paid on a Wednesday, consequently they
 had bought on the next day. No, it was a continuous struggle to make ends meet and they were - they did have to tighten their belts, and probably tightened them more than I realized.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What difference did it make to the family if your father was ill or out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 I can never remember - I can never remember me dad really being ill.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 But he was out of work in 1911?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 It was only - it was only for a - a little while during the strike. Now I don't know how they did that - probably they - they
 - maybe got a shilling or two off the union or might - but you see, they went round with one of these barrel organs and collected pennies off people that had pennies to give, but they got on.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you ever get any help from the guardians or the parish or any charity at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 No, not - there was nothing. I remember - that in the aftermath of the second world war - we was advised to go to the workhouse.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 After the first world war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 After the first world war. That were when - when - a
 million engineers came out, there were - there was no such thing - as - then - if you wanted out you'd to go to the workhouse, well of course - even people that had noting, had pride. More pride than what they have today.-
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You don't remember having to go to the guardians during 1911 when your father was on strike?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
No, no. No, I don't recollect anything of that. And - and I don't recollect that it went on - any length of time. History books from the library would tell how long that went on, it doesn't - it doesn't strike a chord to be of any length of time for me.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
When there was someone in your district whom the people disapproved of very strongly was there any special way in which they showed it, do you remember any one being made to leave by rough music?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well - no. There was really nothing, I - I don't recollect any one in - in the sphere that I moved having either a piano or - there was one person that had a - a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 gramophone}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 , you know, one with a big horn they used to wind up, I used to
 go into their house and - and they used to put me the Blue Danube on and I - I - and they'd put me that on any time I wished, I loved it, it - I wish I had that record today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you remember anyone in the district who for some reason the other people
 disapproved of very strongly, apparently at that time if anyone was disapproved of very strongly they were encouraged to move away from the district by playing what they called rough music, in that they went in front of the house and banged tins and thin
gs together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
No, I don't - I don't recollect it - all that - it was quite - a - a nice little community where we lived. You see, people was more or less all in the same - category, they all more or less lived the same life, they all - they was all on 
short commons - I suppose - between - a certain amount of - of mutual sympathy. Children, ourselves like I mean - well - if we - if we had a Sunday suit and it were better that's it, we might have been a little bit vicious towards each other because one h
a
d something a bit better than others. But it was only child like I don't recollect a lot of it. I certainly don't remember anyone being - annoyed - being driven away or - being driven away or - being regarded as being anything - obnoxious or what like tha
t, no I don't.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 How old were you when you first went to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well - I rather think I went - that the school was supposed to be five. But I have a feeling that I went a little before that. But five was the recognized - time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you go full time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 To school? Oh yes, Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What time did you start in the morning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well, as far as I'm aware I think we used to have to be there nine and then we had what we called dinner at twelve. And - and they used to finish at four, but they use
d to let children come out - quarter to four and in the wintertime, November, foggy, they'd let us come home sometimes before this owing to the fog. Now you must understand at that time that you couldn't see across Keighley because of the smoke - from the
 mills and that. And - when it was foggy it was foggy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What kind of a school was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Ingrow - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 Ingrow}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  council school which is there today. At the end of Queens Road. It was a council school and it - I think there was - it - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 infant\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  classes and it went up to like standard six.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Would that be when you were twelve?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 I went - I - I left at - I left there - half time at twelve and left at thirteen to go }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10574403\charrsid12214547 to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 work full time. And I stayed at that one school all the time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 It was a mixed school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you walk to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 How long did it take you to get there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well, I wouldn't like to say but - I had to walk from Springbank over to - the - quarter of an hour I daresay, it just depends - when we 
set off or whether we wanted go or whether we didn't want to go. If we didn't want to go one of sisters were dragging us, well -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Your sisters would take you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you come home for your midday meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What did you think of school, did you like it or dislike it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
If I said that I liked it - I would probably be telling untruth and at the same time if I said I disliked it I would be. I - I think I took it as part and parcel of a like that I had to accept, this was - something that we had to do and we did it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 How did you feel about the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
I - I got on well with the teachers, I liked the teachers, they was - they was kind and - and if there was anything that you wished to do during that particul
ar lesson then they would encourage you and - and help you. Yes, I - I liked - I liked the - the teachers. I didn't like 'em when they - when they give me cane like for -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did the teachers emphasise certain things as important in life such as manners and tidiness and punctuality, ways of speaking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Yes, oh yes, they - there were certain lessons where they tried to - teach us English. But when it come to speech they didn't make much impression on us there because I mean we were all Yorkshire - diale
ct people and we never really lost it but in studying English we did get the fundamentals of the proper speech. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Had you to be mannerly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes. Yes. They - they - they did and they used to more or less emphasise the - the cleanliness and t
he tidiness of - of keeping the place tidy and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 And yourselves tidy, how about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh - yes, this was a - a general trend.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What about punctuality, had you to be there spot on nine?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 If you weren't - if you weren't it was - hold your hand out. Right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did your parents }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 show}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  an interest in your schoolwork at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Yes, as far as - as far as they could, we - we used to get a report and they'd read it and if we were doing fairly well that was it. The main thing - I - I think I was a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 happy}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  medium, I was never at the top, I was never at the bottom -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did your parents ever visit the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - there was - there was certain times when they used tom - ask the parents to go, me mother used to pop across, I don't - I don't
 recollect me dad going, he never had time you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did the other children come from similar types of home to your own or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well they were all more or less from the same - people, but of course it covered a fair area, they'd be from all types
 of homes and - and all types of - people but the boys and girls and - there was no difference in - and no segregation and ought of that, we was all - part and parcel of the school and that was it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Would you say that the teachers singled out any particular children for different treatment from the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well - not - not particularly, I think that if they did it - it was done - in a different manner to what probably - we would think. The only people that we realized were those that got more cane
 than what we got. That were because they were - ready to - you know, to be - misbehave, and make no mistake, we used to get caned. And we didn't seek a second helping.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You got the cane if you did anything wrong, did the girls as well as the boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Yes. Yes. I - I - I don't say - I don't say that they probably get the same punishment at certain times at the boys got but - they used to get the cane if they misbehaved but of course the misbehaving of boys was a lot different to the girls, I mean - i
f we - if we was told not to go climbing on the top of the outbuildings you can bet your bottom dollar that that's just what we did do. So we got the cane for doing it, then we didn't do it no more. At least we didn't get caught.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Were there any gangs or groups in the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well it - if there was gangs it was only - the boys that came from the different part. I mean, lads that came from Springbank were Springbank. And boys that came from Woodhouse, boys that came from Ingrow Lane. They'd keep to
 theirself and of course if there was any difficulty well there was a free fight in the yard and - and all that. But it - it were never really serious, it was - boys will be boys.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Were there any children who were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 left}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  out of things do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
I can't - I can't really remember a - that there were, it's possible that there could have been - but not as far as we were concerned, I mean - we went to school, we came home for us meals, we - as soon as it were - school had finished, unless we had 
some lines to write we were - home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
When you were twelve you went to work half time and went to work full time when you were thirteen, would you have stayed longer at school if you had had the opportunity?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 If - if the money - if the money had been there probably I would - because - as I }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 began}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
 to - I hated the mill and - I don't think there - were much above two or three shilling a week - for the - the pay we got, I hated the mill, I wanted to come out the mill. Now, I - Loved drawing and I would 
have liked to have stayed to have got more - information, I started to be a little interested in - in mathematics and - and algebra. And - and in - in painting and decorating I would have loved to have been a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 sign writer}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 . But of course - these things - well economic circumstances come, there were three }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3039684\charrsid12214547 more}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  mouths to feed beside mine so it was case of going to mill, I didn't want to go to mill, I didn't like the mill.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You used to go four nights a week for part time education?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 To the Mechanics Institute was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 you took}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Wood - I took woodcarving. And - science of engineering, why I do not know. Then of course then I took - there was - arithmetic and - I forget the other subject. Drawing - yes, drawing. Scale
 drawing and - with a view - I hoped - to come to be like - a draughtsman, but of the whole bottom fell out of that of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you have any regrets at all about your education?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 I have the - I have no regrets in this respect except that - coul
d I do me time over again I would certainly take more notice of the things that was going off in the - in the school - in the council school for the simple reason that why I wasn't really exuberant about going to school the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 moment}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  that I left it I went to -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 As soon as you finished at day school you started at night school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Do you think you benefited from attending school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes. Yes, I - I - I learnt quite a lot, but as I say - had I my time to do over again I would hav
e taken a different - set of course all together. I wouldn't have bothered with wood carving, I would have taken woodwork which I ought to have done. That's a very handy thing to have isn't it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 But do you think you benefited from your day school work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Oh yes. Yes, I - there - there's lots of things. See, I was encouraged to - to do the - the things that I like. I learnt the - the fundamentals of arithmetic and - and reading and writing, I used to be a lovely writer, you know, the old school copy 
type writing, I was considered to be a lovely writer, and - and spelling, I was very good at spelling, unfortunately I don't think I'm as good today as I was then for the simple reason I haven't patience to - to give it too much thought.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 While you were at school did you have a part time job or any means of earning a little regular money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
No. I - I'd nothing of that. I don't know for why but - there was no part time job that I did. And if I did make an extra copper it were probably by going - doin
g a - a bit of shopping for someone or - may be chopping a few sticks or fetching a bit of coal for some person - that probably couldn't afford to pay for it anyway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So you didn't do any work at all until you were twelve when you went half time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 When I went half time. I were a big man when I went half time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 This job that you got half time, how did you get it, did you get it through your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh no, you just - it were just one of those things, I suppose really the - it was a recogni
zed thing when you come to leave school you went and saw these people, you asked to set you on half time. And you went mornings one week, afternoons another. And we used to have to take a - a kind of a - a book with us - that had the attendances and all i
n
 and we did what they call doffing. And - and then when you got from that you got to be - went full time we did what they call jobber, that was taking the full bobbins - off and putting empty bobbins on. And then of course - as I say, I detested every min
ute of the mill and I left and 1914 I think it was. Well the war had broke out - I worked in the mill when the war broke out but just after I went to Darling and Sellers and signed up to be an apprentice turner.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 When you were working this half time what were your hours then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well I think we used to go to work about six o'clock in the morning, we'd half an hour for breakfast, eight o'clock time, and I think it was an hour - for dinner and we used to finish round about half past five going up to six o'clock at night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 When you were half time you'd do the morning part and then another week the afternoons?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 That's right. Afternoon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What about Saturdays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - Saturday morning at one week, we used to Saturday morning one week, when
 we was half time. But it was Saturday morning when you went full time, you'd to work Saturday morning - every week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you get any holidays with pay either when you were half time or full time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 There was no holidays with pay at that time. You got, I think if you were lucky we got six days holidays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What were you paid when you were still going half time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - I cannot remember what I was paid but - I don't think }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 it'd}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  be much above half a crown a week, if it was that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What happened when you went full time, did it increase a great deal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 I'm not really sure as to what pay I did get, I've forgot really what I got. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you feel at that time that it was a fair wage or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - by the - the comments that was m
ade by other people it certainly wasn't. They were slave wages. Slave payment, no one could do really anything about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you give any of the money to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Me mother took it all.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What was it spent on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well of course it's w
ent on food and clothing, - the more that came in there was always clothes you see, something to buy - the money was really needed you see, there was still - when I went to work at thirteen there was still Agnes and David. And Wilf, he hadn't started work
. There were three behind me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 How did you get on with the people at work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 I got on all right with the people at work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What was the firm you worked for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Haggas - Haggas's mill, the spinners - the spinners, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You were a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 doffer}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  then a spinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
That's how - I - I went to what they call doffing and - and then this setting and taking off, I suppose all the names have changed now. And - and first opportunity I got - I was impressed on that I had to have a trade.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 When you'd finished being a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 doffer}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  were you a spinner then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 I never became a spinner. You see - that was a girl - that was a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 girl
\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  employment to - to do the spinning at that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What did you do after you started full time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 The same - the same thing
 that we was doing after - but we went and - full time. But we - we - we - we got the honour of taking some of the full bobbins down into the warehouse. When you got full time, you was a regular, yes, and - and - and the pay - the pay - you can tell that 
it wasn't much because when I signed up for an apprentice at Darling and - Sellers in 19 - back end of 1914 it was only five shilling a week. And that was as a signed apprentice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 How did your employer treat you, Haggas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh they just - they just t
reat - they just treat you as a number and that - that you was there - to run the job and that - and they kept you working and there was no - there was no time for play, it was all work, you was there to work and you'd to work. The overlookers, they were 
pushed by the people over them and the people that was over them were pushed by other people up there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 How did you feel about Mr. Haggas?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 I didn't feel anything particularly about it - him - me sole occupation was that I detested the mill and th
e sooner I could get out of it the better. I daren't - I daren't refuse to go because if I hadn't have gone to work then I would have caught a cold at home with me parents and - they couldn't afford, I mean, if it was only half a crown a week that was mon
ey to them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So you disliked the work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 I - I detested it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 When you were still doing this half time business how did the job alter your attitude to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well I believe - that when I was going to the mill I wished Id been - I was going
 back to school. I rather think I began to like the school better than the work. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Your full time work was still doffing, the same?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Just the same, practically the same, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Your next full time job was as an apprentice?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 How did you get this job, was it through your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well it - the - it was me mother's brother that too, me down to see a Mr Sellers that was over the department at Darling and Sellers Limited, a machine tool turners - machine tool makers 
- and they - bound me over as an apprentice to the turning department which meant that I had to do 'til I was twenty-one. The rate of pay was - five shilling to start with - and I finished me time in 1921 at three days a fortnight and the wages was twenty
-five shillings to finish. That was in - 1921. Now - the - I didn't dislike the work, in this respect. If I say that I was unduly interested to become what you would call a big engineer in a big way, I wasn't, it was a means to an end. And - there was -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you prefer it to the woollen mill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Oh yes, a lot. I liked it better than the mills, I - oh yes. But I wasn't what you cold call really - a settled engineer, I don't know - I wasn't restless, I just couldn't create the interest that I ought to h
ave done. In - having the - the facilities that made the - to my hand if I'd have wished to take it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You were actually a turner were you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What hours did you work at Darling and Sellers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well we started at - around about six o'cl
ock in the morning 'til six at night. We had the usual half hour break breakfast. An hour at dinner time, finish at six.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you have to work Saturday morning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Saturday mornings, we used to work Saturday mornings, I think it was 'til -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you work Sunday at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 No, no Sunday work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you have any holidays with pay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 I don't recollect that - any holidays with pay at that time. We - we got about six days. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 Apprentices}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 , good Friday, we used to run out of the shop, we - it was a - a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 
recognised happening}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
. We - we weren't stopped us pay but - we used to run out and have a half day off at Good Friday - they used to pretend to stop us. But during the war - when the war developed, they did stop it, they stopped all that kind of thing
, we had to work. And we did have to work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 When you were at Darling and Sellers you got five bob a week to start with, what did you think about that, was it a fair wage or not?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - it - it - it wasn't a matter of thinking, this was a - a thin
g that was recognised. That you went as an apprentice and you - you had to obey the rules. You was bound - you'd to take it or leave it, this was part of the set up and - if you served your time you would be given and you'd be a qualified engineer. I have
 papers to that effect. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you give your mother the money still?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Oh yes, me - my mother, I - I gave my wage - all the money that I earned right away up to being twenty-one. I mean - and of course there was spending money - don't ask me }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 what}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  it was 'cos I don't really - remember the amount that I got because - by the time that I was getting up to twenty-one me sisters were working and - and of course - I used to - cadge a bob or two off them.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 How did you get on with the other people you worked with at Darling and Sellers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Very well. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 How did your employer treat you there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well he treat us like what we were. Slaves. To my way of thinking. For the simple reason that I have the recollection of - I worked on a very small lathe. And being bent over doing very fine work it was a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 back aching}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  job. And I remember straightening up - and when I done that I was told to get on with me work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 By the employer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 By the - Mr Darling himself. And he ceased to be friend of mine
 from that day on and all the people that he represented ceased to be friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So you didn't think much about him from that time on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 I didn't - I didn't this - that the amount of - the amount of work that we were doing for the small amount of pa
y that we were getting began to make me realize that there was other jobs that I could do. That - I - the war was on, I was tied, I couldn't do anything about it. They gave me a protection card - which }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 meant}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  that I couldn't be called up to the armed forces
 'til December 1918. I tried to get in what was the Air Force when that come along - and the - in the Flying Corps - that's right, but they wouldn't entertain me because I was an engineer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You did that job until 1921?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Could you tell me what jobs you've done since the first world war, you were a signalman with the railway?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well - in 1918, when the - when the world - when the first world war stopped - there were - most of the people in this country started to become out of work. And
 between 1918 and 1921 when was supposed to be serving me time - it started on three days a week, three days a fortnight and then - we was out of work more than we worked. And the mills, they went the same, three days a week, three days a fortnight. And s
o
metimes not at all. Now, there was a - by this time there was what they called unemployment pay and the unemployment bureau was in what is now a shop down Cavendish Street. And we used to go and queue up to sign on there, I forget, it weren't much money t
hat we got.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So what job did you do from them until you retired?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 And then - when I was twenty-one they allowed me to work - as a few weeks to complete - me time. And I - and I worked three weeks }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 over}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  my twenty-first birthday, they paid me three po
und fifteen a week for those three weeks which qualified me as a full time engineer. And then - I was one of the last to leave there. Now - for the next -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did the place close down then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well, it - it didn't actually close down but there was no 
- what you could call real employment, it was a case of catch as catch could. But they didn't want such as us. However, I went all over to different places, it didn't }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10574403\charrsid12214547 matter,}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  you went into offices, they - they couldn't be civil with you, they were fed up, 
sickened and tired of hearing people wanting a job. The Labour Exchange - they couldn't have cared less because they couldn't do anything about it. There's nobody wanted to bother with you. I went in front of a board to see if I could have an extra few co
p
pers when me unemployment had run out, they told me dad were working and he could keep me. And I got nothing. If I'd any complaints to go to the workhouse. And there were about a million of us all ready to do that. Which my parents wouldn't let me do. And
 
then - in 1922 I'd been all over, I was sickened and tired, I'd nothing in me pocket, I'd nothing only what I stood up in and this was all bought by my parents and me brothers and sisters you know. And God knows they'd - they'd little enough to do. And I 
applied - for a job on the railway. And I got a reply back asking me to go to Derby and I went to Derby, they interviewed me, they told me they hadn't a job but they would keep in touch with me. By the next - day's post there was a letter }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 offering}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  me a job at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 Stretton}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  in Derbyshire - Stretton in Derbyshire - 1922, 24th of August, and I went that day, and reported there. And the wage there was two pound a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 That was quite good at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 It was to me. And I went to a - a lady's house who put
 railwaymen up when they came, there was nowhere else for them to live, and she told me, she said, now I know you'll be working a week for nothing because they held a week back, she said, and you can start and pay your board a fortnight from that time and
 make up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What were you actually doing for the railway?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Then I was portering then. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Which was the railway you were working for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 On the Midland Railway. It was the Midland Railway then at Stretton.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you continue to be a porter then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well - that was the - the lowest form of life that you could start on the railway and - they came and they saw me and they said that if I learned a certain rules and regulations I could work on the Sunday and take charge of the station and t
hat meant another five shillings so I did just that and I got forty-five shillings a week. That five shilling allowed me to come home about once a month. Now from that time - I worked there 'til November and then I went to a little place called Hassop. In
 
the Peak District of Derbyshire. Yes. And this was - was a - railway station that was built - to accommodate the Duke of Devonshire Estate, Chatsworth House and the - the lodgings that I went into was three and a half mile away from the station. And I had
 to walk it there and back. And we worked eight hours a day at that time we'd a guaranteed week. And occasionally we worked a Sunday.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 How long did you continue like this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well I - I was portering, goods portering, general factotum there - fiftee
n months. Then I went to Polterton and Shutton in the mining area. In Derbyshire on the borders of Nottingham. And I met some of the greatest friends with some of the roughest people that ever trod }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 shoe leather}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  and - I was there maybe two year. And I came 
back to Keighley in 1925. And then I went on - porter guarding, as a guard running with the trains to various places, Leeds, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 Ilkley}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 , Worth Valley, shunting, and then in 1934 I set - I went to Oakworth as a signalman. Yes, I started at Oakworth as a signalm
an, I worked at Haworth and Ingrow, a G.N. junction, and then I went from there to - Giggleswick as a signalman. Then from Giggleswick I went to - Altofts and Altofts to Newley and Horsforth, from Newley and Horsforth to Hunslip station, Hunslip station t
o Keighley station junction. Now at that time -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Was this always as a signalman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
This - yes, from there and from 1934 right away up to me finishing in 1965. I'm a signalman. Now me ambition was to become an signalman's inspector. But unfortunately
 - my wife started deteriorating health and just when I was on the threshold of taking the promotion, I brought her back to Keighley where her family and relatives were to five her peace of mind and of course I lost her. I have no regrets I'd do it all ag
ain. And of course I - I kept on. Now when I were sixty-five in the June of 1965 there's the unwritten law that we remained on the job until the end of the holiday season which was the 23rd of October. Now - having a knowledge of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 signalling}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  and all the rule
s and regulations for guards and - everybody, they wanted me to stay on. But I developed arthritis in the leg and believe me there - they were bad at times. And - they offered me to Fri}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 z}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 inghall. Now to go to Frizinghall meant that I would have to be going six days a week, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 travelling}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
 on the bus to get there for - early morning, getting home at half past four at evening time. Late turn I'd be going about eleven o'clock and getting home at half past ten. And so I said, no. I - by the time I finished paying bus
 fares and paid the tax I wasn't going to be much above five pound a week better off. And so I decided to retire. I said, well I'd come through an hard period of life, we've lived harder and - I thought I'd earnt me keep and so if anybody's going to go sh
o
rt of anything it's me. And it - and that's - and I finished work at sixty-five and I draw five pound six pension from the - the government, which is a tremendous amount of - money in this day and age that if you give it to a child he wouldn't even get a 
night out with it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Would you have preferred another type of occupation other than being a railwayman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
No. I would have liked to have started - in the railway as a boy of fifteen, and gone through the clerical side. I - I've always had a - a yen 
or a - a desire to book keeping. I learned a lot of all that, I could do most of all the book keeping and - and that, in the course of me }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 duties}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 . And - I love every minute of the railway work, but I would have loved to have been in charge of a series or an
 area of men, because I - I have the feeling that I was respected and - by the biggest to the lowest. And I've met - I met some of the biggest men in the railway world personally in London and - and even they've come and seen me in the signal boxes and di
scussed various things with me. I have that honour but - unfortunately I didn't get into the sphere that I would have liked.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you belong to a trade union?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes, I was a member of the - now when it started I was when a member of the - I think it
 was the Railway Servants but they changed it to the National Union of Railwaymen. And I }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 joined}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
 the National Union of Railwaymen in 1922 I think it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you take part in any of this activities?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes, I did, I was a member and an active member - inside that movement. I was also a member of the union of Railway }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 Signalman}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
. Which was really a - a silly thing in this respect, in that it was more or less a body of men trying to get recognition through - I mean - because it's obvious that most people
 had no idea what a signalman's work was or what it involved. So I took part - in the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You were a member of the N.U.R.?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 N.U.R. Yes. Union of Railway Signalmen. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you feel that there were divisions of interests among workers, some pe
ople say that in those days there was a great division between trained craftsmen and other workers, did you feel that or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes, yes. You see, the differentials that was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 paid}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  following over the years was a - a big thing, a signalman shall we say had }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 fifty percent}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  more than the porter. Fifty percent was a lot of money, the differentials is gradually lessened and lessened. The incentive to go out has diminished.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Would you say that starting full time work in the mill changed your general attitude to life in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well - in the mill itself I didn't realize, this was a thing that we were brought up to realize that we was going to have to go out to work to earn money. When I became old enough to - to think for myself and worked on the rai
lway I realized that there was a lot of difference between people that was supposed to be doing a lot of work - important work - that as time went on and I learnt these things I realized that there was some fictitious money being paid to people that were 
doing fictitious work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you continue to live at home after you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did starting full time work change your relationship with your parents at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Not really. No, no, no, no difference, it went on the same old sweet way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What about your brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Just the same, expect - except that - as you earnt a little money you - you got the little bit more pocket money. And it weren't much when it was all there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you still go to church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh no, I started to - I started to leave that as I got a bit older - I started to break away from them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you take an interest in politics at all once you'd left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes, when I - when I - I - took an interest politics when I went into t
he engineering. You see, I was - I was a member of the - the - toolmakers at that time and that became incorporated in the A.E.U. Of course when I left the engineers and went onto the railway naturally I joined the N.U.R. the U.R.S. and I took part in pol
itics in regard to trade union movement and - not only that, I went to meetings of the different political parties from - from Communist to Conservatism. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 
I've heard Alec Pollet speak and - you know - and various other speakers that I've forgotten.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 What were your views at that time politically?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - there was a - they was very left wing. Leaning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 This was before 1919?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 This was when I started - I began to be left wing, yes, and I grew more so - more so. I aren't going to say that I was
 a - an - an anarchist or a - or a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 vicious}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
 type but I was definitely left wing in regard to the increase in the standard of living of people who I thought that was earning - the money because I realize as an apprentice in the first place that I was - by th
e time that I was twenty-one that I was earning my keep three times over and making a fearful amount of money for someone else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you feel under any pressure from anybody to support a particular party, perhaps from an employer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 No, no. No, the
re's a lot of - there's a lot of people say that they're compelled to do this and you're compelled to do that. Now, I contributed to the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10574403\charrsid12214547 L}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 abour party by - I think in the first place, when it was first - you agreed to have and it was only a ha'penny a week 
that was stopped out of your pay. Latterly it got to a penny a week. Through the union. Through the - through the union. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 Political}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  affiliation, there was no pressure, it was entirely up to the person themselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Were you a member - as early as 1918 you were paying the political affiliation fee }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 were you}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes, I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So you were actually a member of the labour party then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 I was a - a member of the Labour party, when it comes to - to paying subscriptions and all that there's many a time w
hen I've missed and - and all that kind of thing, like a lot more, it - I've attended the meetings and - and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you ever work for the I.L.P. at that time for an election before 1919?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - oh no, no, not - not to do any real work. No, my - m
ost of my work was done after I went on to the railway. You see, because I - I've worked inside the - the Labour party offices and - you know, with the literature and envelopes, I haven't done any real canvassing, I leave that to others. I was an - I was 
an auditor for the N.U.R. And - assistant secretary - honorary - and - lots of jobs like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
You told me earlier something of how you spent your spare time, did you continue to spend your spare time in the same way or did you have different things to do now, you've already told me you had to go to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 night school}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547  four nights a week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - yes. In the spare time after I joined the railway, now I'm - I'm going now in - this is into the '20's.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 I want between you leaving school and 1919.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 A
nd 1918. Oh in 1919 there wasn't a big lot of difference. You see, the only difference is that I was going to the - the engineering and the night school. And I wasted for nights a week. I played football at - at the weekends with the school, you know, thi
s - I didn't go to school but it was all part of the towns activities. There was numerous football clubs in that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 So you played league football?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 That's right. And then - if I weren't playing - I used to go watch football or go down and watch play cricket.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 When you weren't attending your night school classes where would you go to in the evenings and who would you go with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well, it - it - with - with me mates, we used to be - as I said, we - we'd go for a walk, probably have a talk, 
we were supposed to be in training, we used to go running and - and all that, we'd no real set pattern apart from that. Of course in 1918 when I started to do a bit of courting which she - she became my wife, well of course when I weren't at night school 
I used to go for walks and - and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you ever go to the cinema or anything at this time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Yes, we used to go to cinema, yes, we used to be able to get in for fourpence. And that were a lot of money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you make any new friends, boys or gir
ls at this time, you told me that you met your wife, so she would be a particular girlfriends, did you make any friends with any other boys at this time, perhaps at work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well only - only in - the - the meal breaks or the - the - at work or meeting t
hem shall we say - in - haphazard fashion, I didn't make them friends to go around with. No, I kept me own friends. Right away up to going on to the railway you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you take your friends home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes. Yes, they used to come and go - in fact
, they used to come in and out as like - as though they lived there, I used to go in their houses as though - we lived there, it was all part of the set pattern that started from infancy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 You had a special girl friends, did you have a special boyfriends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 
Well - I had one - one friend, of course he's since died, that - was more or less me constant companion and yet - there was other three or four that was always there, we all started more or less what you could call courting at the same time and -
 we used to meet at the various homes and - and talk and that and - it was mostly walking because you couldn't afford to go to - to the - the pictures and that, there was nobody working. Nobody working.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did your parents meet most of you friends, did they know your friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Oh yes, they knew me friends and me friends parents.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did they expect to know where you were when you went out with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - I should imagine they more or less had an idea where we went because - of the activitie
s that we had it was more or less the same, in the recreation, football, cricket, running, walking and of course at night school, they knew where we were at night school for four nights a week. And in the summer time well of course we was out. And if we w
ere anywhere where we didn't to be that were down in the garden with me dad which I detested, you see, that. All boiled down to the same thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Did you have to be home by a certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - as a child - yes, I - I was expected to be - be home
 - more or less in the winter months on the edge of dark, as it got lighter we were wallowed to stop out, nine o'clock used to be the deadline.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11799755 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Up 'til 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5601259 CT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 Well - when I got up to be eighteen like well of course I got a bit more latitude, I wa
s growing up and - but they used to like to see us in ten o'clock time. Half past ten. No later. And I - I was never one really for keeping }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2235681\charrsid12214547 out }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5005651\charrsid12214547 you see in the days - the theatres used to start, the second turn used to start at - eight forty you see. And th
at it were it. But it was - only used to be high a day and holiday. Pictures the same. Yes, we used to go, we used to go to the theatre. And that's how we did spend what bit of money we did have you see, going to the cheaper seats and - and - both at cine
ma and the - theatre.
\par }}